[Result "*"]

1. c4{ Hello everybody and welcome to this new Chessable course. First of all, let me introduce myself. My name is Danyyil Dvirnyy and I am a Grand Master from Italy. I have represented Italy on several occasions, including 3 Olympiads, European teams’ and individual competitions. More recently, I started my career as a chess coach, helping pupils of various levels from all around the globe.       As you may guess, this course will be about the  1.c4  followed by  2.g3 -setup. Let’s start with talking about some technical ideas for this opening. With the two moves  c4  and  g3 , we are trying to fight for the center without actually committing with our d and e-pawns. Apart from being able to decide how to position these central pawns later on in the game, we secure our king, by defending it with two pieces - the fianchettoed bishop on  g2  and the knight on  f3 . Although this might look obvious, I assure you that it's easier to play when your King is hardly going to be attacked in the initial phase of the game.     Besides the technical ideas of the opening, another purpose of this approach is to sidestep the main lines, deriving from  1.e4  and  1.d4  types positions, so to maintain more playability, even if with the modern theory development, some lines are going to be quite forcing, as well.      Let’s take a quick look at the historical background of this opening. One of the first theoreticians who promoted this opening was the Hungarian Richard Reti, whom these setups oftentimes take the name after. Reti was one of the so-called “hypermodernist” fellas, who basically understood that fighting for the center doesn’t necessarily mean physically occupying the center.      Later on, these strategic concepts were implemented by several Champions, such as Botvinnik, Fischer, and more recently even by Magnus Carlsen himself.  Talking about my experience I approached this opening in a quite funny way. At some point, I played an extremely long blitz match against a friend of mine, who was at the time a specialist in these setups. Although I was able to fight back in those games overall, I couldn’t really get a decent position after the opening with Black, as he was clearly playing by hand, putting into practice the general plans, as I was not familiar with what was going on.     After the match, I started to analyze those ideas deeper, and I really liked them, so after a short period of time, I started to play those ideas myself with White, including classical games. My results were extraordinarily good, and I managed to win some important games with these ideas, for example gaining my Grand Master title and winning two Italian Individual Championships.       Therefore my purpose in creating this course is to provide the reader with versatile opening choices and push them to become an expert in certain types of positions. In my experience, the games coming from this repertoire require a lot of energy from both players, so you can outplay them in the long run.     Now, let’s jump into the action! }
1. e5{ This is the most principled reply, as Black takes space in the center. }( 1...c5 { is the symmetrical English. Here after }2.g3 g6 3.Bg2 Bg7 { Both sides are very flexible and instead of fighting for the central  d2 - d4  or  d7 - d5  breaks, it's more likely that the players will fight for the  b2 - b4  and/or ... b7 - b5  breaks. Personally, I really like these slow maneuvering positions, as one doesn't have to memorize long lines and prioritize general plans. } )( 1...Nf6 { This is the most played, but also a move that doesn't define what Black is going to play. After }2.g3 { Black now can decide whether to develop with }2...e6 ( 2...c6 3.Bg2 d5 { This goes Black to Slav territory. } )( 2...g6 { Black can also go back to some King's Indian stuff fianchettoing the Bishop too. } )3.Bg2 d5 { entering Catalan type of positions. }4.Nf3 { One of the main points of this move order is to avoid the main  4... Bb4 + , which has often times granted Black good positions after the opening. }{ One of the questions one might ask is what happens if Black plays } )( 1...b6 { , basically preventing  2.g3 . White now has to change plans, and this is the only line in the course where White will not fianchetto his Bishop on  g2 . }2.Nc3 Bb7 3.e4 { I think these lines are also quite easy to play for White, although here we try to put a stable grip in the center, by forming a Maroczy bind with the  c4 - e4  pawns. } )
2. g3{ Now Black has several ways to proceed. }
2. Nf6
3. Bg2
3. d5{ This is the standard way of continuing for Black, playing a Reversed Open Sicilian. }( {  A)  }3...Bc5 4.Nc3 O-O { is the closed approach, and once again, it doesn't really pose any problems for White, so we can just develop our pieces, as ... d7 - d5  is not so easy to achieve for Black anymore. } )( {  B)  }3...c6 { is a modern direct approach, and is one of those lines that we need to dissect and be ready to fight against. }4.d4 { is my suggestion, as after }4...exd4 5.Qxd4 { White's Queen is comfortable in the center. } )
4. cxd5
4. Nxd5{ Now in the Dragon line of the Sicilian Defense, the critical way of dealing with it is to castle long in order to create an attack against the King, trying to exchange the fianchettoed Bishop. However, Black can't really do that here, so White is basically set to get those types of positions. }
