1. c4
1. c6
2. g3
2. d5
3. Nf3{ The  c6 - d5  formation is considered to be quite a solid one, aiming against the white Bishop on  g2 . Black will have a choice whether to develop the light squared Bishop out of the pawn chain, or take other paths of development, such as a concrete  dxc4 , or develop the kingside first with  Nf6 - g6 .     On our behalf, we normally prefer to develop our kingside first and then decide on our pawn structure in the center. Usually, the d-pawn is not in a hurry to move, so we remain flexible. }
3. Nf6( { The immediate }3...Bf5 { is countered by }4.Qb3 { , exactly as in the main line, so it's easy to remember. } )
4. Bg2
4. Bf5{ One of the most popular replies. Black develops the bishop outside of the pawn chain, before playing ... e6 . }
5. Qb3( { Back in the day, I was taught that in order to play  Qb3  after  ...Bf5 , White should first exchange on  d5 . However, after }5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Qb3 { in recent years Black proved that the pawn on  b7  can be sacrificed with }6...Nc6! { . Considering that I am not such a brave gentleman to grab these pawns, I prefer not to enter these lines unless it becomes a matter of principle. Here, for instance White has a safe alternative. } )
5. Qc8{ This is considered to be a passive approach. }
6. cxd5{ White opens the c-file and puts pressure across it thanks to the slight lead in development: }
6. cxd5
7. Nc3
7. e6
8. d3{ White keeps the  f5 -Bishop restricted. }
8. Nc6
9. Bf4
9. Be7
10. O-O
10. O-O
11. Rfc1{ After the series of logical moves, White has the advantage. }
