8. a6{ Sooner or later this move has to be played, not only because the pawn is hanging, but also because it discourages White from playing the  b4 - b5  plan. }
9. Bd4{ Not the most natural move, but White has a powerful regrouping here: the bishop will move to  c3 , covering  b4 , and consolidating the queenside. A possibility could still be to push  b4-b5  at the right moment, or to play a plan like  b4  and  Nbd2- Nb3 -Na5 .     On the other hand, it's not so easy to suggest active ideas for Black, the desired  e6 - e5  advance is not so easy to accomplish under good circumstances. }
9. Nbd7{ The most logical continuation. }
10. Bc3{ As intended. }
10. Bd6{ In order to prepare ... e5 , but now White can jump after the  f5 -bishop. }
11. Nh4
11. Bg6{ If Black plays this move directly, then we can simply capture it! }
12. Nxg6
12. hxg6{ And now we play the important move. }
13. h4{ Stopping  g5  and proceed with improving our position slowly, like  e2 - e3 ,  b3 - b4  and once again plans connected to  Nd2 - Nb3 - Na5 , or even preparing some  f2 - f4 /  e2 - e4 - e5  advances. Any reaction from the black side would probably open up our Bishops, so Black should probably just sit and wait, although they remain solid. }
