1. c4
1. e6
2. g3
2. d5
3. Bg2
3. d4{ Black can decide to play this kind of position, with extra space in the center. An important detail here is that White hasn't committed to  b3  yet, which usually would be a half-lost tempo, as White would prefer to play  b2 - b4  in one move. }
4. Nf3
4. c5( { By far the most classical way to manage the position.    In Carlsen - Nepo World Championship 2021, Magnus tried }4...Nc6 5.O-O Bc5 { , so I should mention the game. I believe that White is very comfortable, but it is true that after }6.d3 Nf6 7.Nbd2! { is the precise move.    As often happens, especially on the top level, even such sidelines tend to flow into some concrete lines, as we will discuss it in the course. In general, I would say that this is a risky approach for Black, as if his setup gets pushed backward, he might find himself in a tough situation. } )
5. O-O
5. Nc6
6. e3{ We should contest Black's advanced center, trying to exploit the weak squares, such as  e5  and  e4 . }
6. Nf6( 6...e5 { would be nice for Black, but here it doesn't work as after }7.exd4 exd4 8.b4! { White has a dream version of the Benko-type position. } )
7. exd4
7. cxd4
8. d3{ Without  b2 - b3 , we have the option to develop our bishop to a better square. }
8. Be7( 8...Bc5 { is kind of a weird move, as the bishop will often be under attack after  Nd2–Ne4 . Anyway, after }9.Bg5 h6 10.Bxf6 Qxf6 11.Nbd2 Qd8 12.Qe2! { is strong. White prepares  Ne5  and has an easy game. } )
9. Na3( 9.Re1 { is also possible, but Black can play }9...Nd7 { , preventing  Ne5 . } )
9. O-O
10. Re1
10. Re8{ A useful move, and actually not an obvious one. }( { Now }10...Nd7 { would be a mistake because of }11.Nc2 { and the  d4 -pawn is in danger. Black tried several moves, but I think this line is not so relevant for us because here we just play  Nc2  and prepare  b4 . } )
11. Nc2{ It's unlikely Black will manage to prevent all of White's strategic ideas. }
