[Black "Reverse Maroczy 5...Nc7 - 8.a3 Rb8!? Critical Line #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. c5( { By playing }1...c5 { Black mainly wants to develop the knight to  c6  in order for it to be behind the c-pawn. As many symmetrical openings, we have the move advantage, but should also be familiar with the different structures arising. } )
2. g3{ Traditionally, we prepare to position our bishop on  g2 . Further we will decide on how to develop our minor pieces, although the knight from  b1  will almost always go to  c3 . We can fight for  d2 - d4  or  b2 - b4  pawn breaks, depending on the situation. }
2. Nf6
3. Bg2
3. d5{ The critical approach. Black immediately tries to establish an advantage in the center. }
4. cxd5
4. Nxd5{ Black is trying to establish control in the center, so White has to play energetically. The ideas might include the  b2 - b4 ,  d2 - d4  and eventually  f2 - f4  pawn breaks. }
5. Nc3{ It's important to force Black to take a decision about the  d5 -knight right now. }
5. Nc7{ Once again, this is the main move. Alternative retreats provide White extra options. This is the main reply, which will be covered in depth. Black wants to prepare  e7-e5  and eventually support it with  f7-f6 . }
6. Nf3
6. Nc6
7. O-O
7. e5{ Once Black pushes our back against the wall, we must fight back, otherwise structure-wise Black would be simply better. }
8. a3{ Threatening  b2 - b4 . }
8. Rb8( { This was known to be the best response a long time ago. I remember once I talked about this line with Fabiano Caruana, and he told me that at this point Black is probably slightly better. He won an important game against Veselin Topalov in the first round of the Sinquefield Cup of 2014, the same legendary tournament where Fabiano had the astonishing 7/7 start.    Anyway, going back to the move }8...Rb8 { , Black defends against  b2-b4 , and at the same time removes the rook from the  h1-a8  diagonal, preparing  ...b6  in the future. However, things are far from being so easy. }8...Bg4 { The computer kind of move. The idea is bizarre, after }9.h3 { Black wants to capture on  f3 . }9.h3 Bxf3 10.Bxf3 {    I don't think it's worth analyzing this position too deeply, because no human would give the bishop pair for no apparent reason. White will follow with the  b2–b4  plan, but now can also play positionally, as the light-squared bishop has huge potential. } )
9. Rb1( 9.b4 { would be met by }9...cxb4 10.axb4 Bxb4 { and }11.Nxe5 { doesn't work because after }11...Nxe5 12.Qa4+ Nc6 13.Bxc6+ bxc6 { the  b4 -bishop is protected by the rook on  b8 . } )
9. f6( 9...Be7 10.b4 { once the bishop spent a tempo on  ...Be7 , we have to go for  b2–b4 . } )
10. Qc2( {  A)  The immediate }10.e3 { would be met by }10...Bf5! { , so we defend against this idea first, and free the  d1 -square for the rook. } )( {  B)  }10.d3 { is the most played move here but after }10...Be6 11.Be3 Be7 12.Ne4 b6 { I think Black should be fine. } )
10. Be6
11. e3
11. Bc4{ Black wants to prevent  d2 - d4 . Of course we don't bother sacrificing an exchange. }
12. d4
12. Bxf1
13. Bxf1{ The light squares are extremely weak. }
13. cxd4
14. exd4
14. exd4( 14...Nxd4 15.Nxd4 Qxd4 { would allow the winning move }16.Nb5!  )
15. Nb5
15. Nxb5
16. Bxb5
16. Rc8( 16...Be7 { would be met by }17.Bc4!  )
17. Bd2
17. Qd5{ Black has to find these hard only moves. }
18. Qd3
18. Kd8{ Another super engine move. }
19. Re1{ Black will still struggle to find a place for the king. }
