[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Symmetrical Vigorito Line #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. c5( { By playing }1...c5 { Black mainly wants to develop the knight to  c6  in order for it to be behind the c-pawn. As many symmetrical openings, we have the move advantage, but should also be familiar with the different structures arising. } )
2. g3{ Traditionally, we prepare to position our bishop on  g2 . Further we will decide on how to develop our minor pieces, although the knight from  b1  will almost always go to  c3 . We can fight for  d2 - d4  or  b2 - b4  pawn breaks, depending on the situation. }
2. g6{ With this move Black chooses to slowly develop pieces, instead of going for a quick central control with  ...Nf6  and  ...d5 . }
3. Bg2
3. Bg7
4. Nc3
4. Nc6{ These moves are generally played almost automatically, as  c3  and  c6  are the natural squares for the knights. }
5. a3{ This is what I suggest for White throughout the course. Here we will see how to fight against the  d6 - e5  setup, which in my opinion is slightly dangerous strategically for Black, but also ambitious if Black manages to get what they want.     I called it the Vigorito setup, because the American International Master David Vigorito made a course about it here on Chessable. He is a well established author in the chess world. This setup is usually used by ambitious and aggressive players who like space. However, we have our own aces up our sleeves too. }
5. d6{ This is usually the safest move, not allowing  b2 - b4 . Black can also start with ... a7 - a5 , as it is generally their idea not to care too much about the  b5 - d5  weaknesses, as they count on covering those with their pieces later on. }
6. Nf3( { White can sometimes develop the knight via  Nge2 , but it's seldom combined with  a2-a3 .    I should mention that }6.b4?! { doesn't work here as after }6...cxb4 7.axb4 { Black can capture the pawn }7...Nxb4! 8.Qa4+ { doesn't give White much as after }8...Nc6 9.Bxc6+ bxc6 10.Qxc6+ Bd7 { Black defends and ends up with an extra bishop. } )
6. e5{ Even though this move obviously weakens the  d5 -square, Black counts on playing ... Nge7 , ... Be6  and ... d5  and claim the dominance over this square in the long run. }
7. O-O
7. a5( { Now it's time to stop  b2-b4 . If }7...Nge7 8.b4! { It's time to strike with this move. } )
8. d3( { We defend the  c4 -pawn in advance and prepare our next important idea.    The typical }8.Ne1 { in order to drive the knight all the way towards  d5  via  e1–c2–e3  would be imprecise because of }8...Be6! 9.d3 { White has to lose this tempo to defend the  c4 -pawn. Black will play  ...d5 , before the  e1 -knight can barely get close. }9...Nge7 10.Nc2 d5! 11.cxd5 Nxd5 12.Ne3 { White managed to apply pressure on the  d5 -knight, but after }12...Nb6! { Black showed good results. } )
8. Nge7( { If Black would have played }8...h6?! { White would continue with }9.Ne1 { The typical knight regrouping and after }9...Be6 10.Nc2 Nge7 { Now Black covered the  Bg5 -idea, but Black is not in time to play  ...d5 , as White manages to control it after }11.Ne3 { . } )
9. Bg5{ I think this move is not only objectively a good one, but provides White with an easy position to play. }
9. f6{ As a matter of principle, Black should play this move. }
10. Bd2{ preparing to support  b2 - b4  in the future. }
10. O-O
11. Ne1{ A typical move, rerouting the knight. }
11. Be6
12. Nd5( { We have to play this move to stop  d5  physically. In case of }12.Nc2 d5! 13.cxd5 Nxd5 14.Ne3 { Black showed no problems after }14...Nxe3 15.Bxe3 Nd4! { In Aronian - Dominguez, 2010. Capturing the pawn with }16.Bxb7 { provides Black with excellent play after }16...Rb8 17.Bg2 f5! { and White shouldn't allow this. } )
12. Bf7{ Preparing to capture on  d5  with the knight, as there is no fork with the bishop on  f7 . }
13. Nxe7+
13. Qxe7
14. Nc2{ Intending both  Ne3  and  b4 . Black can't prevent both ideas. }
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Symmetrical Vigorito Line #2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. c5( { By playing }1...c5 { Black mainly wants to develop the knight to  c6  in order for it to be behind the c-pawn. As many symmetrical openings, we have the move advantage, but should also be familiar with the different structures arising. } )
2. g3{ Traditionally, we prepare to position our bishop on  g2 . Further we will decide on how to develop our minor pieces, although the knight from  b1  will almost always go to  c3 . We can fight for  d2 - d4  or  b2 - b4  pawn breaks, depending on the situation. }
2. g6{ With this move Black chooses to slowly develop pieces, instead of going for a quick central control with  ...Nf6  and  ...d5 . }
3. Bg2
3. Bg7
4. Nc3
4. Nc6{ These moves are generally played almost automatically, as  c3  and  c6  are the natural squares for the knights. }
5. a3{ This is what I suggest for White throughout the course. Here we will see how to fight against the  d6 - e5  setup, which in my opinion is slightly dangerous strategically for Black, but also ambitious if Black manages to get what they want.     I called it the Vigorito setup, because the American International Master David Vigorito made a course about it here on Chessable. He is a well established author in the chess world. This setup is usually used by ambitious and aggressive players who like space. However, we have our own aces up our sleeves too. }
5. d6{ This is usually the safest move, not allowing  b2 - b4 . Black can also start with ... a7 - a5 , as it is generally their idea not to care too much about the  b5 - d5  weaknesses, as they count on covering those with their pieces later on. }
6. Nf3( { White can sometimes develop the knight via  Nge2 , but it's seldom combined with  a2-a3 .    I should mention that }6.b4?! { doesn't work here as after }6...cxb4 7.axb4 { Black can capture the pawn }7...Nxb4! 8.Qa4+ { doesn't give White much as after }8...Nc6 9.Bxc6+ bxc6 10.Qxc6+ Bd7 { Black defends and ends up with an extra bishop. } )
6. e5{ Even though this move obviously weakens the  d5 -square, Black counts on playing ... Nge7 , ... Be6  and ... d5  and claim the dominance over this square in the long run. }
7. O-O
7. a5( { Now it's time to stop  b2-b4 . If }7...Nge7 8.b4! { It's time to strike with this move. } )
8. d3( { We defend the  c4 -pawn in advance and prepare our next important idea.    The typical }8.Ne1 { in order to drive the knight all the way towards  d5  via  e1–c2–e3  would be imprecise because of }8...Be6! 9.d3 { White has to lose this tempo to defend the  c4 -pawn. Black will play  ...d5 , before the  e1 -knight can barely get close. }9...Nge7 10.Nc2 d5! 11.cxd5 Nxd5 12.Ne3 { White managed to apply pressure on the  d5 -knight, but after }12...Nb6! { Black showed good results. } )
8. Nge7( { If Black would have played }8...h6?! { White would continue with }9.Ne1 { The typical knight regrouping and after }9...Be6 10.Nc2 Nge7 { Now Black covered the  Bg5 -idea, but Black is not in time to play  ...d5 , as White manages to control it after }11.Ne3 { . } )
9. Bg5{ I think this move is not only objectively a good one, but provides White with an easy position to play. }
9. O-O{ This allows White his main idea. }
10. Bxe7{ We exchange this sort of superfluous bishop in order to fight for the light squares. }
10. Nxe7
11. Rb1{ Our plans will be connected to the  b2 - b4  push, and the control of the central light squares, such as  e4  and  d5 . Furthermore, Black struggles to create any play without his extra knight. }
11. Be6( { Preparing  d6-d5 . Now after }12.Ng5 Bc8 { I don't see a bright future for the  g5 -knight, apart from getting back on track with }13.Nf3 { . } )
12. Nd2{ A typical move, opening the diagonal for the  g2 -bishop. }
12. d5{ If not now, probably never. }
13. cxd5
13. Nxd5
14. Nc4{ White is threatening to exchange everything on  d5 , followed by the  Nb6  fork. }
14. Rb8{ Kind of forced. }
15. Nxd5{ White start the exchanging operation. }
15. Bxd5
16. Bxd5
16. Qxd5
17. e4
17. Qd8
18. Ne3{  Nd5  next gives White an easy position to play. Surprisingly enough, the engine is not very enthusiastic for White, but generally Black is not happy with such an outcome of the opening. }
