1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. Nf6
3. Bg2
3. d5{ The evergreen main approach. Black takes space in the center, playing the so called 'Open Reversed Sicilian'. In my experience, White is usually happy to see this on the board, as he is a tempo up playing with White. Additionally, from the Black's side it takes a dose of bravery to enter this kind of setup. However, this is the most popular line from Black, and as many people tend to follow the mainstream continuations, here we go. }
4. cxd5
4. Nxd5
5. Nc3{ White has other move orders, but here we will examine the most classical approach from White. }
5. Nb6{ By far the main move. }
6. Nf3
6. Nc6
7. O-O( 7.b4? { Doesn't work as after }7...Bxb4 8.Nxe5 Nxe5 { White doesn't have the  Qa4  check. } )
7. Be6{ Would be a dubious move. Black tries to play  ...Qd7  followed by long castle, in the dragon fashion. However, White has a strong reply, thanks to this extra tempo. }
8. d4{ Black has no time for his plan. }
8. exd4( 8...Nxd4 9.Nxe5 { would leave Black with concrete problems on the  h1–a8  diagonal, and with some serious development issues as well. } )
9. Nb5{ White has a strong initiative. }
