2. c6{ The Keres variation has become extremely popular nowadays. Black tries to build a strong center by supporting his  d5 -push with the  c6 -pawn. Having played  g3 , we already have a clear plan of fighting it, by placing our bishop on  g2 . }
3. d4{ This is what I suggest in this course. White strikes in the center, as the  c6 -pawn will now take away the square for the Knight in order to kick a potentially strong Queen in the center if the  d4 -pawn gets captured. }
3. Bb4+
4. Bd2
4. Bxd2+
5. Qxd2
5. d6{ Having exchanged the dark-squared bishop, Black positions the pawns on the dark squares. We will see how White will be able to proceed here. }
6. Nc3{ As this knight will certainly be placed on  c3 , we start with this move. }
6. Nf6{ Black surely doesn't want to release the tension in the center and keeps developing. }
7. Bg2{ Another developing move, stopping ... e4 , that might be a strategical idea for Black. }
7. O-O( 7...Qe7 { is possible, threatening  e5–e4 . }8.e4 { We stop  ...e4  and control the center. } )
8. dxe5{ This simplifies White's play. }
8. dxe5
9. Qxd8
9. Rxd8
10. Nf3{ Developing with tempo. Surprisingly enough, this position is not so easy as it seems for Black. White has some concrete ideas, which shouldn't be underestimated. }
