6. f3( { We have to start shaking the Black pawn formation. As a rule of thumb, Black shouldn't capture on  f3  unless it is needed, and here they have an interesting alternative, which is }6...Nf6 { . } )
6. f5{ May come to mind, but it turns out once again to be a strategic mistake. Black takes away squares for the pieces and renders White's development easier. Nevertheless, White has to be precise. }
7. Nh3{ First we develop the knight as it will be surely developed on  h3 . }
7. Nf6
8. cxd5
8. cxd5
9. Bg5{ Threatening  Bxf6  followed by  Nf4 . }
9. Be6
10. Nf4
10. Bf7
11. Bh3{ A healthy habit of delaying the development of the  g1 -bishop. We will see that this idea will be useful in several other lines. }
11. g6{ Black has to defend the pawn. }
12. O-O
12. exf3( { Black has to release the tension. In case of }12...O-O { White undermines the pawn chain by playing }13.g4! { with an amazing initiative. } )
13. Bh6{ Another important finesse. }
13. Bf8( { This sad move turns to be the best option for Black here. In case of the greedy }13...fxe2 14.Qxe2 Nc6 15.Rae1 { Black's king is left in the center and after the logical }15...Ne4 { White follows up with }16.g4! { opening the position. } )
14. Bxf8{ White simply trades the bishops. }
14. Kxf8
15. exf3
15. Kg7
16. Qd2{ White ends up with a tiny, but a pleasant positional advantage. }
