1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. c6{ The Keres variation has become extremely popular nowadays. Black tries to build a strong center by supporting his  d5 -push with the  c6 -pawn. Having played  g3 , we already have a clear plan of fighting it, by placing our bishop on  g2 . }
3. d4{ This is what I suggest in this course. White strikes in the center, as the  c6 -pawn will now take away the square for the Knight in order to kick a potentially strong Queen in the center if the  d4 -pawn gets captured. }
3. e4{ This ambitious move broke in the opening charts, becoming the modern main line. Black aims to build a strong center. }
4. a3{ This is what I will advice here. We take away the  b4 -square from the  f8 -bishop and count on fighting Black's center later on. White will rely on the  f2 - f3  break if needed. }
4. d5
5. Nc3
5. Be7{ This is the move GM Arturs Neiksans suggests in his chessable course. Black doesn't hurry to develop his  g8  Knight and plays a development move. }
6. f3( { We have to start shaking the Black pawn formation. As a rule of thumb, Black shouldn't capture on  f3  unless it is needed, and here they have an interesting alternative, which is }6...Nf6 { . } )
6. Nf6
7. Bg2
7. exf3( { Generally Black has to react by taking on  f3 , although here }7...O-O { is a serious alternative, which will be discussed in depth in the main course. } )
8. Nxf3
8. dxc4{ This option will be possible for Black during the next few moves. In this case we would react by occupying the center. }
9. O-O
9. O-O
10. e4{ Generally at this point Black has to expand on the queenside. }
10. b5
11. h3{ This is a healthy move to gain some space on the kingside, improve our king and eventually start placing our pieces on the kingside, such as the bishop on  f4 .     The position is unbalanced and both players have their chances. However White has a strong center and Black has to be careful, as the center might be pushed forward at any moment, opening lines. }
