6. O-O
7. O-O
7. Nc6{ Not allowing  b2 - b4  at the moment, this is the most played move here. }
8. Rb1{ White proceeds with his plan. It's much better to start with  Rb1  instead of  a3 , for two reasons: first we take out the rook from the  a1 - g7  diagonal, so no  e4  funky stuff is possible opening the  g7 -bishop; secondly, in case Black doesn't play ... a5 , but after  b4  will play ... a6 , we can play  a2 - a4  there in one move. }
8. a5{ Forcing  a2 - a3  in order to play  b4 . This way Black will open the a-file for his rook. }
9. a3{ White should insist in playing  b2 - b4 . The plans with  b2 - b3   Bb2  might be a little bit too slow compared to the Karpov System, where Black doesn't have a clear on the kingside. }
9. h6{ Preparing ... Be6 , is a typical move here for Black. }
10. b4
10. axb4
11. axb4
11. Be6
12. b5
12. Ne7{ More of a standard reply and by far the most played move here. }( { After }12...Nd4 { we go for }13.Ne1! { a pattern to have in mind. The d4-knight might turn out to be cumbersome. After }13.Nxd4 exd4 14.Ne4 Nxe4 15.Bxe4 { White would have a favorable structure, if it wasn't for }15...d5!= { when Black equalizes. } )
13. Bb2{ The most played move. White wants to connect the Rooks and play  Ra1 , as it is usually their main idea. }
13. Qd7{ Black prepares ... Bh3 . }
14. Ra1( { There is no need to play }14.Qc2 { , as we can recapture on  a1  with the queen and later  Qa7  would be annoying. } )
14. Bh3( 14...c6 { would allow a thematic response from White: }15.bxc6 bxc6 16.c5! { and White damage Black's central structure. } )
15. Rxa8{ A prosy, but strong decision. }
15. Rxa8
16. Qb3{ Preparing  Ra1 . White has little extra space on the queenside and without the heavy pieces, as the Rooks will most likely be traded along the a-file, we will hardly face any serious threats on the kingside. }
