9. h6{ This is generally a useful move, preparing  Be6  without having to worry about the  Ng5  jumps. }( 9...Be6? { would be a mistake because of }10.b5! c5 11.Ng5! Bc8 12.Nge4 { and  c5  is lost, as  b7 - b6  can't be played. } )
10. b5{ We can go for it now! }
10. c5
11. Ne4{ We are forcing the following line now. }
11. Nd7
12. Ba3
12. b6{ Our  b5 -pawn is very annoying. Eventually, we'll remove our pieces from the a-file and push  a4 - a5 . Maybe even  a6  at some point. }
13. Nd6
13. Qc7
14. Nd2
14. Rb8
15. Nxc8{ We grab the Bishop pair, and Black has no central play. }
15. Rbxc8
16. Rae1{  e2 - e3  or  e2 - e4  is actually an important move to know in these positions, but once you know you should play it, it becomes easy to play. I played a very nice game with a similar structure against GM Oleg Korneev. }
