2. d5
3. Nf3{ The  c6 - d5  formation is considered to be quite a solid one, aiming against the white Bishop on  g2 . Black will have a choice whether to develop the light squared Bishop out of the pawn chain, or take other paths of development, such as a concrete  dxc4 , or develop the kingside first with  Nf6 - g6 .     On our behalf, we normally prefer to develop our kingside first and then decide on our pawn structure in the center. Usually, the d-pawn is not in a hurry to move, so we remain flexible. }
3. g6{ This move order allows Black to play  e7 - e5  once they played  Bg7  instead of  Nf6 . }( { Therefore we shouldn't just play }4.Bg2 { and sort of just fall back into standard setups. } )
4. Qa4{ I feel like this move is pretty interesting and worth trying, as White's play is far more natural in my opinion. First of all, we threaten to take on  d5 , so Black has to react somehow. }
4. dxc4( { This seems to be the best reply. }4...Nd7?! { would be followed by }5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Bg2 Bg7 7.O-O Ngf6 8.Nc3 O-O 9.d3 { +/=, when the  d7 -Knight is quite misplaced. } )
5. Qxc4
5. Bg7
6. Bg2
6. e5{ This is Black's idea. Now I think it's important to start with the next move. }
7. d3( { If }7.O-O Ne7 8.d3 O-O 9.Bd2 { Black is in time to play }9...h6! 10.Qc1 Kh7 { . } )
7. Ne7( { If }7...Be6 8.Qb4 { is annoying, as Black doesn't really want to weaken the long  h1 - a8  diagonal by playing }8...b6 { . If }8...Qe7 { to try to castle, then }9.Qa5!? { and Black still has issues to solve. } )
8. Bd2{ This is the point. White wants to create the  Bd2 - Qc1  battery before Black managed to play  h6 - Kh7 . }
8. O-O( { Black can start with }8...h6 9.Qc1 Be6 { , but they won't be able to castle in the next few moves unless they play  g6 - g5 .    For example: }10.O-O Nd7 11.Nc3 Rc8 12.h4!? { makes it difficult for Black to play  g6-g5 . } )
9. Qc1
9. Na6( { I don't believe a human would easily play }9...Bg4 10.h3 Bxf3 { as I see no reason to give up the Bishop pair. } )( 9...Nf5 { makes more sense to prepare  h7 - h6  and to bring the Knight to  d4 . }10.h4!? { This move is our theme in this kind of position. We try to provoke }10...h5 { . }( { ( }10...h6 { is met by }11.g4 { and  Bxh6 , with an attack). } ){ After }10...h5 11.O-O Nd4 12.Re1 Bg4 13.Nxd4 exd4 14.Bg5 { we notice the importance of the inclusion of  h4 - h5 .  f7 - f6  would be a huge weakening move for Black. } )
10. Nc3
10. Nc7{ Somehow this manoeuvre is often seen with a pawn on  c6 . }
11. h4{ Once again we include this idea. }
11. h5{ Black shouldn't allow  h4 - h5  }
12. O-O{ Now that we got our structure on kingside, we go back to basics. I would like to show the viewer how Black can get in trouble easily with kind of natural moves. }
12. Be6( { Other moves are also possible, but the character of the position doesn't change. Probably something like }12...Ned5 { would be objectively stronger. } )
13. Bh6{ Exchanging fianchettoed Bishop should usually be followed by an attack against the King, but here we exchange the Bishops because the  f6 - g5  squares and the  e5  pawn would be weaker without them and on the other hand the  d4  square is controlled by the  f3  Knight, or might be controlled by the  e3  pawn. }
13. Bxh6
