1. c4
1. c6
2. g3
2. d5
3. Nf3{ The  c6 - d5  formation is considered to be quite a solid one, aiming against the white Bishop on  g2 . Black will have a choice whether to develop the light squared Bishop out of the pawn chain, or take other paths of development, such as a concrete  dxc4 , or develop the kingside first with  Nf6 - g6 .     On our behalf, we normally prefer to develop our kingside first and then decide on our pawn structure in the center. Usually, the d-pawn is not in a hurry to move, so we remain flexible. }
3. Bg4( { This is definitely a more precise move order, compared to }3...Nf6 { . Black hurries up in order to reinforce the central structure with  e7-e6  and keeps the developing flexibility for the kingside light pieces. } )
4. Bg2
4. e6
5. cxd5( { We take this decision exploiting the momentum, as the move }5...cxd5 { is not possible because of }6.Qa4+ { , winning the bishop on the spot. While }5...Bxf3 6.Bxf3 cxd5 { is considered to be the most solid continuation for Black, here we will discuss }5...exd5 { , leading to an asymmetrical structure. } )
5. Bxf3
6. Bxf3
6. cxd5{ Of course this was the idea of capturing the Knight on  f3  first. }
7. O-O
7. Nc6{ This is another point of Black's play. By playing  4...e6  first, he has the  c6 -square for the Knight. If Black would have played  4...Nd7 , this would have been a much worse square for the Knight. }
8. Nc3( { We start with this move, without committing our structure in the center yet. In the case of }8.d4 { , Black has a surprisingly strong move: }8...f5! { which was played in a game Artemiev - Petrov. Once the structure in the center is defined, this move makes perfect sense. Apparently, it's not so easy for White to deal with it. }( { First of all a logical }9.e3?! { would already be a mistake, because after }9...Nf6 { White's King could suddenly become a target. } ){ Therefore White should play }9.Nc3 { but after the precise }9...Bd6! { Black looks healthy. Not }9...Nf6 { as White can exchange this dangerous Knight with }10.Bg5!  )
8. Nf6
9. d4{ Once Black has put his Knight on  f6 , we can play  d4 , as  f7 - f5  isn't there anymore. }
9. Be7( { This is the most-played reply. In the case of }9...Bd6?! { , White can break in the center with }10.e4! { and after }10...dxe4 11.Nxe4 Nxe4 12.Bxe4 O-O 13.d5! { the Bishops provide an obvious advantage. } )
10. e3
10. O-O{ This is a fairly standard position and it is clear that both sides are very solid and a long manoeuvring will follow. As we are not going to discuss any direct lines, I would like to recommend a new move here for White, with a slightly unusual regrouping. }
11. Re1{ The idea is fairly simple - we want to transfer our from  e2  to  c2 , at the same time freeing the  e1  square for the Bishop, which is very typical. }( { Furthermore, we avoid the move  Nd7 - Nb6  manoeuvre, as here after }11...Nd7 { White plays }12.e4! { with advantage: }12...dxe4 13.Bxe4 Nf6 14.d5! exd5 15.Nxd5 Nxe4 16.Rxe4 { and the rook is useful on the e-file.  Let's try to analyze several plans for Black in this position. } )
11. a6{ This is a typical move, in order to expand on the queenside. We continue with our plan. }
12. Re2
12. b5{ Although this is logical, I think this move is slightly inaccurate. On the other hand, it's coherent with the move 11... a6 . }
13. Bd2
13. Qb6{ Generally Black wants to keep the pawns on  a6 - b5  to have some space and eventually double his Rooks on the c-file, or to reroute his Knight via  a5 - c4 . }( 13...b4?! { would be a strategic mistake, as after }14.Na4 { the  c5 -square would be juicy for White. } )
14. Be1
14. Rfc8
15. Rc2{ Next will be  Ne2 - Nf4 - Nd3 . I don't claim that White has an advantage here, but they have reached a harmonious setup in the quickest possible way and they have a clear strategical target: the  c5 -square. }
