[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. c6
2. g3
2. d5
3. Nf3{ The  c6 - d5  formation is considered to be quite a solid one, aiming against the white Bishop on  g2 . Black will have a choice whether to develop the light squared Bishop out of the pawn chain, or take other paths of development, such as a concrete  dxc4 , or develop the kingside first with  Nf6 - g6 .     On our behalf, we normally prefer to develop our kingside first and then decide on our pawn structure in the center. Usually, the d-pawn is not in a hurry to move, so we remain flexible. }
3. Bg4( { This is definitely a more precise move order, compared to }3...Nf6 { . Black hurries up in order to reinforce the central structure with  e7-e6  and keeps the developing flexibility for the kingside light pieces. } )
4. Bg2
4. e6
5. cxd5( { We take this decision exploiting the momentum, as the move }5...cxd5 { is not possible because of }6.Qa4+ { , winning the bishop on the spot. While }5...Bxf3 6.Bxf3 cxd5 { is considered to be the most solid continuation for Black, here we will discuss }5...exd5 { , leading to an asymmetrical structure. } )
5. exd5
6. O-O
6. Nf6{ Black should probably play this move firsthand, both in order to be one step forward to castling and to add a defender of the  e4  square, as  e2 - e4  is White's main strategic plan. }
7. d3( { White starts preparing  e2-e4  with this development move. }7.h3 Bh5 { would be a great inclusion for White, but Black can play }7...Bxf3 8.Bxf3 Bd6 { , placing the Bishop on this best diagonal without having to deal with  e2-e4 , as the pawn is still on  d2 . That's why we start with the move }7.d3 { first, to discourage }7...Bd6 { . } )
7. Bd6{ Allows the immediate and strong reply. }
8. e4
8. O-O
9. h3
9. Bxf3
10. Qxf3{ White gets a very comfortable version of this structure. }
10. Nbd7
11. Nc3{ The Bishop on  d6  is not as active as on  c5 . }
11. dxe4
12. dxe4
12. Qe7
13. Qe2{ White is ready to roll his pawns with  f4 - e5 . }
