[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. c6
2. g3
2. d5
3. Nf3{ The  c6 - d5  formation is considered to be quite a solid one, aiming against the white Bishop on  g2 . Black will have a choice whether to develop the light squared Bishop out of the pawn chain, or take other paths of development, such as a concrete  dxc4 , or develop the kingside first with  Nf6 - g6 .     On our behalf, we normally prefer to develop our kingside first and then decide on our pawn structure in the center. Usually, the d-pawn is not in a hurry to move, so we remain flexible. }
3. Nf6( { The immediate }3...Bf5 { is countered by }4.Qb3 { , exactly as in the main line, so it's easy to remember. Black will probably respond with the typical }4...Qb6 { , when we can simply capture on  b6  - }5.Qxb6 axb6 6.cxd5 cxd5 { . If }6...Bxb1 { then }7.Rxb1 cxd5 8.a3 { and we have a pleasant structure for White with two Bishops. After }6...cxd5 { we proceed with }7.Nc3 Nf6 8.Nd4! { and the White Knight lands on  b5 , gaining a tempo on the  f5 -Bishop. }8...Bd7 9.Ndb5 Na6 { . White has a pleasant plus thanks to the weakness of the  b5 -square. } )
4. Bg2
4. Bf5
5. Qb3( { Back in the day, I was taught that in order to play  Qb3  after  Bf5 , White should first exchange on  d5 , however after }5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Qb3 { , in recent years Black proved that the pawn on  b7  can be sacrificed with }6...Nc6! {    Considering that I am not such a brave gentleman to grab these pawns, I prefer not to enter these lines, unless it becomes a matter of principle, but here White has a safer alternative. } )
5. Qb6
6. d3{ White is not in a hurry and prepares the move  Be3 , in order to remove the strong black Queen from  b6 . }( { In the case of }6.cxd5 { , Black would capture himself on  b3  - }6...Qxb3 7.axb3 cxd5 { , where White might have some edge thanks to the open  a -file, but recent games showed that Black is objectively fine, although I would still prefer White. } )
6. e6{ Apart from being a developing move, Black is now ready to recapture on  d5  with his e- pawn, which is usually a healthier option. }( { My engine insists on playing }6...Bg4 { , but it's hard to take such a move seriously, as it simply loses a tempo. Apart from }7.Be3 { , where after }7...Qxb3 8.axb3 Bxf3 { this turns out to be the engine's idea and we sort of transpose to the main line positions.    White can even switch to a calmer game by playing }7.Qc2 { and slowly improve as Black's Bishop on  g4  is hardly better placed than on  f5 . Even the logical }7.Ne5 { is possible, when once again the goal is just to trade Black's poorly judged light-square Bishop is anyhow possible and play }7...e6 { as if nothing happened. Not surprisingly, no human hand has played the  6...Bg4  move in a real game so far. } )
7. Be3
7. Qxb3( { If Black tries to fix the structure by playing }7...dxc4?! { , White will play }8.Qxc4! { , obtaining a favourable pawn structure. The only for Black to justify the 7th move is to capture the  b2 -pawn with }8...Qxb2 { , but after }9.O-O! { They can't capture the Rook on  a1 , as they lose the Queen after }10.Bd4 { , and in case of a stronger }9...Nd5 { White follows up with }10.Bd4 Qxe2 11.Qb3! Nb4 12.Ne1! { when it becomes clear that Black has exaggerated in capturing venomous pawns. } )
8. axb3
8. a6{ Sooner or later this move has to be played, not only because the pawn is hanging, but also because it discourages White from playing the  b4 - b5  plan. }
9. Bd4{ Not the most natural move, but White has a powerful regrouping here: the Bishop will move to  c3 , covering the  b4  and consolidating his queenside. A possibility could still be to push  b4 - b5  at the right moment, or to play a plan like  b4 - Nbd2 - Nb3 - Na5 . On the other hand, it's not so easy to suggest a plan for Black, as the desired  e6 - e5  advance is not so easy to accomplish under good circumstances. }
9. Nbd7( { One of the two logical continuations. Black can either try to prepare  e6 - e5  as soon as possible, or invest a tempo in }9...h6 { , in order to save the life of the  f5 -Bishop. White would still proceed with }10.Bc3 { and after }10...Nbd7 11.Nbd2 Be7 ( { ( }11...Bd6 { would also be possible, but if Black plays }9...h6 { they are probably going to be more solid and the Bishop on  d6  might be more vulnerable than on  e7 ). } )12.O-O O-O 13.b4 { in this position White's plan is fairly simple - we want the Knight to reach  a5  via  b3 . In the case of }13...dxc4 { we can recapture with the Knight as a possible  e2 - e4  will be useful and the loneliness of the b-pawns is compensated by the enthusiasm of White's pieces. } )
10. Bc3{ As intended. }
10. Bd6{ This is a logical move in order to prepare  e6 - e5 , but now White can jump after the  f5 -Bishop. }
11. Nh4
11. Bg4( { If Black plays directly }11...Bg6 { , we can simply capture it and after }12.Nxg6 hxg6 { play the important }13.h4! { move, stopping  g5  and proceed with improving our position slowly, like  e2 - e3 ,  b3 - b4  and once again plans connected to  Nd2 - Nb3 - Na5 , or even preparing some  f2 - f4 / e2 - e4 - e5  advances. Any reaction from the Black side would probably open up our Bishops, so Black should probably just sit and wait, although they remain solid. } )
12. h3
12. Bh5
13. g4
13. Bg6{ In different lines in chess, provoking  h3 - g4  in order to capture the Bishop is an improvement for the Bishop's side, but this concept is usually referred to a position with the Queens on the board and to King safety. Here White can consider these two moves more like an expansion of the kingside, rather than a weakening of the position. }
14. Nxg6
14. hxg6( { It has to be said, that after }14...fxg6 { , it is important for White to fight for the dark squares, by playing }15.g5! { and after }15...Nh5 16.Nd2 { White will eventually get a very harmonious setup after  e2 - e3 / Ke2  and  h4 , with a pleasant advantage. } )
15. Nd2
15. O-O-O
16. e3{ Once again, thanks to his potential  b3 - b4 / d3 - d4 / f2 - f4  advances, White keeps things under control and can improve his position in many ways, while it's hard to say the same on Black's behalf. Here  g6 - g5  is not a big issue, as the Bishop is perfectly placed on  g2  and not only controls the long  h1 - a8  diagonal, but at the same time defends the  h3  pawn, leaving the possibility for the  h1  Rook to move without worrying about it. }
