5. b3
5. Bg7
6. Bb2( { It is important that we can play this move exactly at this moment. }6.O-O { , which would be a transposition from another order of moves, would allow }6...Ne4! { giving Black a comfortable play. } )
6. O-O
7. O-O{ Here Black has two main plans: first is to try to fight for  e7 - e5 , and the other is to remain solid with  e7 - e6 . Both plans can be executed with  Bg4 - Bxf3 , or with the light-squared Bishop still alive. Let's see the options. }
7. Re8{ Black wants to play  e7 - e5  at once by supporting it with  Re8  and  Nbd7 . }( 7...a5 { , as usual, is met by }8.a3 { intending on }8...a4 { to respond with }9.cxd5 { followed by  b3-b4 , with a better structure. } )( { It's also possible to play }7...Nbd7 { and shift to a different development after }8.Qc2 b6 { intending  Bb7 . Here we should go }9.d4 Bb7 10.Nc3 e6 { and prepare  e4 . Compared to other lines, we are more comfortable preparing  e2 - e4  under the best circumstances, for example, positioning our rooks in the center with  Rad1 - Rfe1 . } )
8. Qc2{ We are preparing against the  e7 - e5  plan by keeping the central pawns on  d2  and  e2  and hurrying up with counterplay. Our idea is to meet with  cxd5 , and in the case of  cxd5  we will try to create threats along the open c-file. }
8. Nbd7{ Transposes to 7... Re8 . }
9. Nc3( { I played }9.Rc1 { in the game against Alexey Sarana in World Blitz Championship and got a very promising position. The idea is to meet }9...e5 { with }10.cxd5 { and in case of }10...cxd5 { to invade with }11.Qc7 { . Although I believe Black should be fine there, Alexey took with the Knight on  d5  and I felt very comfortable.    }9.Nc3 { is a more logical move.    }9.d4 { is, of course, a possibility, but by playing it Whites fixes the structure in the center. Sometimes we can (and should!) play  d2 - d4 , but here I would like to suggest a more typical English-style pawn structure. } )
9. e5
10. cxd5
10. Nxd5( { Black should recapture with the Knight, as if }10...cxd5 11.Nb5! { White has strong threats: }11...Re6 12.Qc7! ( { (not }12.Nc7?? { because of }12...Rc6! { ) } )12...Qe8 13.Rfc1! { and  Nd6  is coming. } )
11. d3{ We reached a structure typical for the open English. It seems that Black has strange-looking pieces, so let's try to figure out how we could rearrange them. }
11. Nxc3( { This exchange seems the most logical to me. If Black plays }11...Nb4 12.Qb1 { , White will always have the  b4 - b5  plan, and Black will still have to find good squares for the pieces. } )
12. Bxc3
12. Nb6{ The Knight is heading towards  d5  square. }
13. Bb2
13. Nd5
14. a3{ A typical improving move. We take out the  b4 -square and prepare  b3 - b4 . }
14. a5( { Stopping  b4 . Black can also ignore it and play something like }14...h6 15.b4 { , but I prefer White. They have plans of  b4 - b5  or the typical combo in the center  e2 - e4  connected to  d3 - d4  right after it. } )
15. Rfd1{ White prepares  e2 - e4  and  d4 . }
15. Nc7( { I think this is something that Black can have as an improving pattern: the Knight goes to  b5 , which is a strange square, but apparently quite a good one. Now }16.e4?! { would be a positional mistake, as after }16...Bg4! { The  d4  advance would be impossible and the  d4 -square would simply be weak. } )
16. e3
16. Qe7{ Definitely not the only move, but a move that doesn't alter the character of the position. }
17. h3( { Black has several possibilities, but generally White is happy as they can always go for  d3 - d4 , or to play  e3 - e4  followed by  d3 - d4 , avoiding }17.d4 e4! { Black has a weak  b6 -square, which might be an issue in some lines. } )
