[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. c6
2. g3
2. d5
3. Nf3{ The  c6 - d5  formation is considered to be quite a solid one, aiming against the white Bishop on  g2 . Black will have a choice whether to develop the light squared Bishop out of the pawn chain, or take other paths of development, such as a concrete  dxc4 , or develop the kingside first with  Nf6 - g6 .     On our behalf, we normally prefer to develop our kingside first and then decide on our pawn structure in the center. Usually, the d-pawn is not in a hurry to move, so we remain flexible. }
3. Nf6( { The immediate }3...Bf5 { is countered by }4.Qb3 { , exactly as in the main line, so it's easy to remember. Black will probably respond with the typical }4...Qb6 { , when we can simply capture on  b6  - }5.Qxb6 axb6 6.cxd5 cxd5 { . If }6...Bxb1 { then }7.Rxb1 cxd5 8.a3 { and we have a pleasant structure for White with two Bishops. After }6...cxd5 { we proceed with }7.Nc3 Nf6 8.Nd4! { and the White Knight lands on  b5 , gaining a tempo on the  f5 -Bishop. }8...Bd7 9.Ndb5 Na6 { . White has a pleasant plus thanks to the weakness of the  b5 -square. } )
4. Bg2
4. g6
5. b3
5. Bg7
6. Bb2( { It is important that we can play this move exactly at this moment. }6.O-O { , which would be a transposition from another order of moves, would allow }6...Ne4! { giving Black a comfortable play. } )
6. O-O
7. O-O{ Here Black has two main plans: first is to try to fight for  e7 - e5 , and the other is to remain solid with  e7 - e6 . Both plans can be executed with  Bg4 - Bxf3 , or with the light-squared Bishop still alive. Let's see the options. }
7. Bg4{ Once the Bishop lands on this square, it will be certainly traded for the  f3 -Knight, as after  h3  you can't play  Bh5  with the pawn on the  g6 , as after  g4  you would lose it. }
8. d3{ White remains flexible, preparing  Nbd2 . }
8. Bxf3{ It makes sense to exchange the Knight right now, before White would play  Nbd2  and recapture with the other Knight. }( 8...Qc8 9.Nbd2 Bh3 { is not a great plan, as after }10.Rc1 Bxg2 11.Kxg2 { , White has a strategic threat of }cxd5 { and after }11...Qd8 12.Qc2 { Black lost too many tempis. White will proceed with the usual  b4 - b5  plan, as in other variations. } )
9. Bxf3
9. Re8{ Preparing  e7 - e5  in one move. }( 9...e6 10.Bg2 Nbd7 { would be similar to the  8...a5  variation. } )
10. Bg2{ A useful move, removing the Bishop from an uncomfortable position. }
10. e5
11. Nd2( { There is no need to rush with }11.cxd5 { , as the Knight is still on  b8 , so we can wait. } )
11. a5
12. a3{ We already know this pattern from the other lines. }
12. Bf8{ Once again, a familiar regrouping. Apart from preparing  Bd6 , Black defends against the  b3 - b4  threat. }( { In the case of }12...Nbd7 { we could capture on  d5  }13.cxd5 cxd5 14.Rc1 { , getting a similar position where the idea of  h4-Bh3  are there. Another idea here is to regroup the Knight to  c3  via  b1  with  Nb1 . } )
13. e3
13. Nbd7{ I guess sooner or later this move has to be played. }
14. cxd5
14. cxd5
15. Rc1{ Although Black occupies the center, it might become quite shaky, being under the fire of the two fianchettoed Bishops. The  b5  square is also a possible destination for the white Knight. Black has to be careful. }
