3. Nf3{ The  c6 - d5  formation is considered to be quite a solid one, aiming against the white Bishop on  g2 . Black will have a choice whether to develop the light squared Bishop out of the pawn chain, or take other paths of development, such as a concrete  dxc4 , or develop the kingside first with  Nf6 - g6 .     On our behalf, we normally prefer to develop our kingside first and then decide on our pawn structure in the center. Usually, the d-pawn is not in a hurry to move, so we remain flexible. }
3. Nf6( { The immediate }3...Bf5 { is countered by }4.Qb3 { , exactly as in the main line, so it's easy to remember. Black will probably respond with the typical }4...Qb6 { , when we can simply capture on  b6  - }5.Qxb6 axb6 6.cxd5 cxd5 { . If }6...Bxb1 { then }7.Rxb1 cxd5 8.a3 { and we have a pleasant structure for White with two Bishops. After }6...cxd5 { we proceed with }7.Nc3 Nf6 8.Nd4! { and the White Knight lands on  b5 , gaining a tempo on the  f5 -Bishop. }8...Bd7 9.Ndb5 Na6 { . White has a pleasant plus thanks to the weakness of the  b5 -square. } )
4. Bg2
4. e6
5. b3{ We simply defend the  c4  pawn. }
5. Nbd7{ This is the most flexible move. Black will decide later on how to develop his dark-squared Bishop. They can either play  Bd6  in order to prepare  e5 , or develop with  b6 - Bb7 , where the Bishop will be better placed on  e7 . }
6. d4( { Preventing  e5 . It's a finesse not to develop the dark-squared Bishop with }6.Bb2 { as it is too early. } )
6. Be7
7. O-O
7. O-O
8. Nc3{ Once again, we don't rush with the development of the  b2  Bishop. }
8. b6{ Logical development. }
9. Qd3
9. Bb7
10. Rd1{ We prepare against  c6 - c5 , in order have a Rook on an open file. }
10. Re8( { This seems to be the best setup. Black waits until  Bb2  and plays  Qc7-Rad8 , preparing  c6 - c5 , or even  e6-e5  in some cases. The direct }10...c5 { has been tried a few times. After }11.cxd5 Nxd5 12.Nxd5 Bxd5 13.e4 Bb7 14.d5 ( { (I like the move }14.d5 { instead of the most played }14.Bb2 { ) } ){ We create a passed pawn. Black should play }14...exd5 15.exd5 Bf6 16.Rb1 Re8! { So after }17.Bf4 { they can play }17...Nf8 { . This position looks promising. Apart from the direct }18.b4 { , White can actually improve with other moves, for example }18.h4 { . Black will have to be careful against the passed pawn. } )( { The move }10...Rc8 { means that Black will play  Qc7-Qb8-Rfd8  before playing  c6-c5 . This gives us time to play }11.Bb2 Qc7 12.Rac1 { . After }12...Qb8 13.Nd2! Rfd8 { is not really working because of }14.e4 { and Black is not in time to make  c6-c5  work. After }14...dxe4 15.Ndxe4 Nxe4 16.Nxe4 c5?! 17.d5! { White is clearly better. } )
11. Bb2( { If we play }11.Bf4 { , Black plays the typical }11...Nh5 { and we have no better than to play }12.Bc1 { . } )( 11.e4 dxe4 12.Nxe4 c5 13.Nxf6+ Nxf6 14.Bf4 cxd4 15.Nxd4 Qc8 { is usually fine for Black. } )
11. Qc7
12. Rac1
12. Rad8
13. cxd5{ Exploiting the fact that Black can't recapture with the c-pawn. }
13. exd5( { If }13...Nxd5 { , than }14.e4 { and White has a plus because of the central control. } )
14. e3{ Preparing  Ne2 . }
14. Bf8{ Not the only move, but one that sooner or later has to be played. }
15. Ne2{ We reach a complex position with almost all the pieces on the board. White will try to apply pressure over the c-file, while Black will try to play on the kingside, where White is well protected. Black can also play  c5  at some point, but I would be rather happy with White to face  c6 - c5 , because my pieces would open up, especially the Bishop on  b2 . White will double on the c-file,  Nf4 - Qe2 - Nd3  is another manoeuvre to consider. }
