6. Nb6{ Black has to put a grip on the  c4  pawn, otherwise White would be just better. }( 6...b5 { is possible. }7.b3! { Usually once Black plays  b7 - b5 , we can play  b3  for compensation. }7...cxb3 8.Qxc6 { Here we can grab the pawn immediately. }8...Rb8 9.axb3 { Black counts on finishing the development, but I feel like White's central pawns should grant us an edge. }9...Bb7 10.Qc2 Rc8 11.Qa2 { . Even if it's not the dream square for the Queen, after }11...a6 { we want to play }12.Ba3 { . Our center is very mobile and I think it's easier to play with White. } )
7. Na3
7. Be6{ Once again, defending the  c4  pawn. }( 7...g6 8.Nxc4 Nxc4 9.Qxc4 { is just better for White, as they will take the center with  d4 - e4 . } )( { An early }7...Qd5 { is well met by }8.b3! { After }8...cxb3 9.axb3 { White is threatening  Nc4 . To proceed with development, Black has to play  g6 , immediately or after }9...Be6 10.Rb1 { . The main line can be }9...g6 10.Nc4 Qd8 { . Bad sign for Black's plan now is }11.Nfe5! { Threatening  Nxc6 . White has the initiative and  Na5  is also a future idea, paralyzing the queenside. } )
8. Ne5( 8.b3 { would be quite pointless, as after }8...cxb3 9.axb3 g6 { Black seems to be faster in development. As  Ne5  wasn't possible after  7...Qd5 , we play it now. } )
8. h5{ The latest fashion, and definitely the strongest move in my opinion. }
9. h4( { I would be tempted to try this move, because in Sam Shankland's course he suggests }9...Ng4 { , which to me seems like a slight inaccuracy. } )
9. Qd4
10. Nf3{ We have to retreat. }
10. Qe4( 10...Qd7 { would still be followed by }11.b3 { . } )
11. Qd1{ I think White has the initiative. Next will be  b2 - b3  and then try to open up the position against the Black's underdeveloped setup. You can check out the example game  Yilmazyerli - Dolgun, 2022.  }
