10. Re1( { This patient Rook move is important for White in order to fight for an advantage. We don't want to hurry with the  d2 - d4  advance, as after }10.d4 cxd4 11.Nxd4 { Black would exchange our potentially powerful  g2 -Bishop. That's why we prepare the  d2 - d4  push by shutting the  h1 - a8  diagonal with our  e2 - e4  advance, so that our  g2 -Bishop would still be alive. A typical procedure for the  h1 - a8  diagonal Bishops' warfare. } )
10. Be7( { If Black tries to stop the  d2-d4  advance by playing the }10...Nbd7 11.e4 e5 { sequence, White can switch plans and simply play }12.d3 { with the following  Nh4  and  Nf5/Nd5  plans, when the pieces are very powerful. White can also include the  a2 - a4  move in order to prevent the  b7-b5  expansion as I did in a couple of my games, although it is not strictly necessary. } )
11. e4
11. O-O
12. d4{ White succeeded with their idea. }
12. cxd4{ Not so many alternatives to suggest for Black. Anyways White simply wants to develop the remaining pieces on the queenside. }
13. Nxd4
13. Qb6{ This is Black's best continuation, as they try to put immediate pressure on the  d4 -Knight with  Rd8 . }
14. Nb3{ I like this simple move. White anticipates the threat of  Rd8  and prepares  Be3 . }( { A more aggressive alternative is }14.Be3 { sacrificing the  b2 -pawn - }14...Qxb2 15.Ncb5! Bxb5 16.Rb1 Qxa2 17.Rxb5 { White is two pawns down, but Black hasn't developed the queenside and there is a threat of  e4 - e5  - opening the strong  g2 -Bishop. Therefore Black has to play }17...Nc6 { giving up the  b7 -pawn, but solving the development issues. White can still play }18.e5 { , but Black should be solid enough to parry possible threats. } )
14. Rd8
15. Qc2( 15.Qe2 { is also possible, but Black has a strong reply }15...Qa6! { and I feel that White should keep more pieces on the board, as we have a space advantage in the center. In a blitz game I tried here }16.Qc2 { , following this concept, when White will gain a tempo with  Bf1  and after  Qb6   Be3  will follow. With all the pieces on the board, White should have an edge. } )
15. Na6( { This is Black's main idea to have some counterplay. In the case of the standard }15...Nbd7 { , White gets what they want after }16.Be3 Qc7 17.Rac1 { , and the pieces are harmoniously developed. This position is what White is aiming for in this variation. } )
16. Be3( { There is no time for }16.a3 { , as after }16...Nc5 { Black manages to exchange a piece and solve the problems. } )
16. Nb4{ A very important intermezzo. }
17. Qe2
17. Qa6{ Once again Black is trying to exchange some pieces. Even if White can't really avoid the Queen's exchange, we can still play a sequence that can guarantee us a certain pressure. }
18. Qxa6
18. Nxa6( 18...bxa6 19.Rad1 { gives Black the possibility of jumping on  d3  with the Knight, but it's not worth it comparing the weakness of the double a-pawns. } )
19. a3
19. Ng4{ If Black doesn't play this active move, White could play  h3  to prevent it, and eventually expand with  f4 - e5 , with a pretty clear advantage. }
20. Bd4
20. e5( { Once again trying to force matters. }20...Kf8 { is possible with the idea to defend the  e7 -Bishop and threaten  e6 - e5 , but after }21.h3 { the complications will lead to an easier position to play with White: }21...e5 22.hxg4 exd4 23.Nd5 { and now }23...Bxd5 24.exd5 Nc7 25.Rad1 { is no fun for Black. } )
21. Nd5
21. Bf8( { If }21...Bxd5 22.exd5 { and }22...exd4 { would be a mistake because of }23.Rxe7 { with advantage. } )
22. Bc3{ In a rather symmetrical position structure-wise, White has better pieces. }
22. b6{ The most logical move to prevent  Na5 . }
23. Nb4{ Not an intuitive thing to move away the strong Knight on  d5 , but Black is forced to capture. }
23. Nxb4
24. axb4
24. Nf6
25. Nd2{ Once again, White plays for two results, with the ideas of putting pressure along the a-file, or rerouting the Bishop via  f1  to  c4 . }
