4. Nf3
4. c5( { In the Carlsen - Nepo World Championship 2021, Magnus tried }4...Nc6 5.O-O Bc5 { , so I should mention the game. I believe that White is very comfortable, but it is true that after }6.d3 Nf6 7.Nbd2! { is the precise move. Somehow some sort of forcing line arises after }7...a5 8.Nb3 Be7 9.e3 { undermining the center. }9...dxe3 10.Bxe3 Ng4 11.Bc5!? { an important move to keep the initiative.    In the game White could have had an advantage after }11...O-O 12.d4 a4 13.Bxe7 Qxe7 14.Nc5 e5 { is an improvement for Black, but I believe White is better coordinated and the  c5 -Knight is an asset. } )
5. O-O
5. Nc6
6. e3{ We should contest Black's advanced center, trying to exploit the weak squares, such as  e5  and  e4 . }
6. Nf6( 6...e5 { is premature, as after }7.exd4 exd4 8.b4! { is strong. }8...Nxb4 { is met by }9.Ne5! ( { ( }9.Re1+ Be7 10.a3 { and we get a great version of a Benko type gambit, where the play along the open a and b files, together with the active pieces on the kingside, should provide White with more than enough initiative). } ){ and if }9...Bd6 10.a3 { gives White a strong plus. } )
7. exd4
7. cxd4
8. d3{ Without  b2 - b3 , we have the possibility of developing our Bishop on a better square. }
8. h6{ This is logical to prevent  Bg5 , but it costs Black a tempo. }( {  A)  }8...Bc5 { is kind of a weird move, as the Bishop will often be under attack after  Nd2-Ne4 . Anyway after }9.Bg5 h6 10.Bxf6 Qxf6 11.Nbd2 Qd8 12.Qe2! { is strong. We prepare  Ne5  }12...O-O 13.Ne5 Nxe5 14.Qxe5 ( { (After   }13...Qc7 14.Nxc6 bxc6 15.Nb3 Be7 16.Nxd4 Bf6 { according to the engine Black has compensation, but I would not be happy to play this with Black. Of course they have two Bishops, but the position is rather closed. We can play }17.Nb3 { and slowly improve). } )14...Qd6 15.Qxd6 Bxd6⩲ { was a dream endgame for White in Jakovenko - Eljanov, 2015. } )( {  B)  }8...Be7 9.Na3 ( { ( }9.Re1 { is also possible, but Black can play }9...Nd7 { , preventing  Ne5 ). } )9...O-O 10.Re1 ( { (Now }10...Nd7 { would be a mistake because of }11.Nc2 { , and the  d4 -pawn is in danger. Black tried several moves, but I think this line is not so relevant for us, because here we just play  Nc2  and prepare  b4 . For example in Ding - Korobov, Black played }10...Ne8 { , in order to build the  f6 - e5 - d4  pawn chain and after }11.Nc2 f6 12.b4 { Black was already worse. }11...a5 { is better, but we can even go back with  Na3 - b5 . White has an easy game). } )10...Re8 11.Nc2 { . } )
9. Bf4{ This is definitely the best try. }
9. Nd7( { Once again, after }9...Bd6 10.Bxd6 Qxd6 11.Re1 O-O 12.Nbd2 { I would rather be White. We exchanged a minor piece and have a harmonious development. } )
10. Re1
10. Bc5( 10...Bb4 { is recommended, but I don't see the point after }11.Nbd2 a5 12.a3 { . } )
11. Nbd2{ We are planning to play  Nb3 . }
11. g5{ This is, as you can guess, the correspondence approach. }( { The human }11...O-O { is well met by }12.Nb3 { as after }12...Bb4 { we have }13.Re4! Nf6 14.Re2 { and  Ne5  next, with advantage. } )
12. Be5
12. O-O{ I think it's not likely to get this position in an over the board game. Anyway the correspondence game went on after: }
13. Ne4
13. Bb4{ If Black plays ... g5  and doesn't have anything concrete, I mean, winning some material, I don't see the point. }
14. Bd6
14. Bxe1
15. Nxe1
15. f5( { This exchange sac has been played in correspondence games. }15...Re8 16.Qh5 { , followed by  h4  and  Nf3 , highlights the problems of the ... g5  push. } )
16. Bxf8
16. Qxf8
17. Nd2{ And once again I think it's obvious that White is preferable here. Imagine: in other lines we want to provoke Black into weakening their kingside, and here they did it voluntarily! }
