[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. e6
2. g3
2. d5
3. Bg2
3. Nf6
4. Nf3{ The advantage of this setup against  e6 - d5  is that we avoid the  Bb4 + Catalan, and remain flexible to decide how to react. }
4. dxc4
5. Qa4+
5. c6
6. Qxc4
6. b5{ Black tries to solve his queenside problems first. }
7. Qb3( 7.Qc2 { is a popular retreat. The difference between }7.Qc2 { and  7.Qb3  can be seen in the variation }7...Bb7 8.O-O Nbd7 9.d4 c5! { With the Queen on  b3 , Black will have to spend a tempo for  a7 - a6 , in order to protect the  b5 -pawn before they get to play  ...c5 . } )
7. Bb7
8. O-O{ I think this is a more challenging move order for Black. }
8. Nbd7
9. d4{ We prepare the  Ne5  jump. }
9. a6( 9...Be7 { this is probably a transposition, but White has some extra options, such as }10.Nc3 { , or }10.Rd1 { . } )( 9...c5? { simply loses a pawn after }10.Qxb5± { . } )
10. Ne5{ Preventing  c6 - c5  in the first place. }
10. Nxe5{ Black doesn't really have good alternatives. }
11. dxe5
11. Nd5{ Black's best move. At first, I thought this would run into  Rd1  followed by  e4  ideas. That's a common misconception. White's best plan involves leaving the  e4 -square available for the minor pieces, especially the knight. }
12. Nc3{ Putting pressure on  d5 , so  c6 - c5  is not possible. }
12. Be7{ Black once again develops, not caring about the  e5  pawn. }( 12...c5? { is well met by }13.Rd1+- { and Black has concrete problems with the  d5 -square. } )
13. Ne4{ Alluding to some  Nd6  in the future. It's important that 13... c5  here would be a mistake. }
13. c5
14. Bg5( { Removing the  e7  defender. }14.Rd1 c4 { grants Black a great position. Luckily, we have a tactical refutation of ... c5 . } )
14. O-O{ This loses on the spot. }
15. Nxc5{ Another important tactical point. The Bishop on  e7  is pinned and the one on  b7  is hanging. }
