1. c4
1. e6
2. g3
2. d5
3. Bg2
3. Nf6
4. Nf3{ The advantage of this setup against  e6 - d5  is that we avoid the  Bb4 + Catalan and remain flexible to decide how to react. }
4. Be7{ Black ignores the tension in the center and aims to finish development first. }
5. d4
5. O-O
6. Qc2( { Creates more chaotic positions, in order to unbalance the game.    The idea behind this move is to prevent the direct }6...dxc4 { . We also postpone the short castle, so in some cases, we can end up castling long.    If Black doesn't react we are likely to expand in the center with  Nbd2-e4 , or complete the development in a harmonious way with  b3-Bb2 . However, our queen on  c2  might be misplaced, so positions with imbalances might arise, and we should be ready to play some interesting, double-edged positions.    The  6.Qc2  lines give you play in order to win many games, but it also involves more risk. } )
6. dxc4( 6...Nbd7 { will probably transpose to }6...c6 { with a solid approach. } )
7. Qxc4
7. a6
8. Ne5
8. b5
9. Qd3{ Black can't play  Bb7 , so White has an edge. }
