12. Ne1{ A strange move, but quite a typical pattern against the undefended  b7 -Bishop. }( 12.cxd5 cxd4 13.Nxd4 Nxd5 14.Nf5 Nxc3 15.Nxe7+ Qxe7 16.Bxc3 Bxg2 17.Kxg2 { this position was reached in Fridman - Maghsoodloo, Abu Dhabi 2021. }17...Nf6 18.Qb2 Rfd8 19.Bxf6 gxf6 20.Rac1 Kg7 21.Rxd8 Qxd8 22.Rxc8 { 1/2-1/2 Fridman, D (2626) -Maghsoodloo, P (2701) Abu Dhabi 2021 with an easy draw. } )
12. cxd4
13. Rxd4
13. Bc5{ Not the only move, but this have been played in a correspondence game and is quite logical. }( 13...Re8 14.Rad1 { Black should still proceed with }14...Bc5 { and we kind of enter the line with  13...Bc5 . } )
14. Rdd1( 14.Rh4!? { this is possible, but the Rook on  h4  seems rather misplaced to me. } )
14. Ba8{ Defending the Bishop. }
15. cxd5{ Now that the  a8 -Bishop is defending, we release the tension in the center. }
15. Nxd5
16. Qd2( { As we can't play }16.Nxd5 { because of }16...Bxf2+ { , we have to play this. Still, Black is slightly uncoordinated. } )
16. Nxc3{ This is of course a serious alternative. }
17. Bxc3
17. Bxg2
18. Kxg2
18. Nf6
19. Qxd8( { Keeping the Queens with }19.Qf4 { is also possible, but going to a pleasant endgame is also logical. } )
19. Rfxd8
20. Bxf6
20. gxf6
21. Rxd8+
21. Rxd8
22. Rc1{ Next will be  Rc2  and  Nd3 , with a pleasant endgame. }
22. Rd2
23. Rc2
23. Rxc2
24. Nxc2{ Although objectively the endgame should be equal, I would pick White here. }
