9. dxe4{ Kind of a good news for White, as our  g2  Bishop gets some fresh air. }
10. Nxe4
10. Bb7{ Black is trying to go for  c5 . I think generally this is quite a risky approach, as Black will end leaning on the edge trying to survive. }
11. Nc3{ In my opinion a more sound practical approach. We prepare to answer  c6 - c5  with  d4 - d5 . }
11. c5{ This move will have to be played sooner or later. 11... Rc8  is an alternative, but we will still have  d4 - d5  in case of an upcoming  c6 - c5 . }
12. d5
12. exd5
13. cxd5{ White is left with a very dangerous 'd' pawn, as Black has no clear way to block it safely. }
13. Bd6{ This kind of the only move, otherwise White plays  d5 - d6 . }( { Black has no time to play }13...Ne8? { as after }14.Re1 Nd6 15.Bf4 { they would be stuck without being able to develop any other piece. } )
14. Re1{ A pretty uncomfortable situation for Black, as they often has to take care of the  d5  passed pawn. White can regroup the  f3  Knight via  h4  to  f5  or via  d2  to  c4 . Sometimes even sacrificing the d-pawn might be an idea, as White pieces would be very active once Black would capture it under unfavourable circumstances. }
