4. Nf3{ The advantage of this setup against  e6 - d5  is that we avoid the  Bb4 + Catalan, and remain flexible to decide how to react. }
4. Be7{ Black ignores the tension in the center and aims to finish development first. }
5. d4
5. O-O
6. Nc3{ This move doesn't expose the Knight, as it goes to a good central square. Generally, the drawback of this move might be that the  c4 -pawn is not defended, as we will see in the next chapters. On the other hand, White puts immediately pressure over Black's center. }
6. dxc4{ The most direct approach. }
7. Ne5{ This is our idea before castling. }
7. c5{ This move usually leads to an endgame. As  d4  is under attack, White has to capture on  c5 . }
8. dxc5
8. Qxd1+
9. Nxd1
9. Bxc5
10. O-O( { Here several moves have been tried. We can recapture the pawn immediately, }11.Ne3 { has been trendy. We go down the main road. } )
10. Nd5
11. Ne3{ This is the move that I recommend, putting immediate pressure on  d5 . }
11. Nxe3
12. Bxe3
12. Bxe3
13. fxe3{ Although we ruined our kingside structure, our aces lie on the queenside, so we are not bothered. }
13. c3{ This move also has to be played, otherwise White has a development advantage basically for free. }
14. bxc3
14. f6
15. Nd3{ White has a clear play against the  b7 -pawn and the extra ideas might be  Rf4 - Rc4 , or simply  Rb1  and  c4 - c5 . Black still has to prove to have equality. }
