[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. e6
2. g3
2. d5
3. Bg2
3. Nf6
4. Nf3{ The advantage of this setup against  e6 - d5  is that we avoid the  Bb4 + Catalan, and remain flexible to decide how to react. }
4. Be7{ Black ignores the tension in the center and aims to finish development first. }
5. d4
5. O-O
6. Nc3{ This move doesn't expose the Knight, as it goes to a good central square. Generally, the drawback of this move might be that the  c4 -pawn is not defended, as we will see in the next chapters. On the other hand, White puts immediately pressure over Black's center. }
6. Nbd7{ This is the solid approach for Black, together with 6... c6 . }
7. Qd3{ The difference is that White can now place the queen to a more active square. }
7. b6{ The most ambitious follow-up. Black wants to play the moves  Bb7 - c5  spending the minimum time possible. 7...  c6  would kind of transpose to 6... c6  line. }
8. cxd5{ Generally this is the typical response to  b7 - b6  move. As the  c6  square is now weakened, we can open the c-file. }( 8.Ne5 { achieves nothing, as after }8...Bb7 9.O-O c5 { Black is perfectly in time to blow up White's center. } )
8. Nxd5{ Definitely the best try. }( 8...exd5 9.O-O Bb7 10.Bf4 { leads to a typical position, where White is supposed to be better. The plan is to place the Rooks along the c and d-files and try to put pressure in the center with the  Ne5 - e4  plan. } )
9. O-O( 9.Nxd5 exd5 { this helps Black as after  Re8 - Bf6  White's plans connected with  Ne5 - e4  will be hardly possible in practice. } )
9. Bb7
10. Rd1{ White prepares  e2 - e4 . }( 10.e4? { would be a blunder because of }10...Nxc3 11.bxc3 Nc5! { and Black wins a central pawn. } )
10. Nxc3
11. bxc3( 11.Qxc3 Rc8 { it would be hard for White to reach the  c6 -square now. } )
11. Nf6{ Black has to do something against  e2 - e4 . }
12. Ne5{ Following our plan. }
12. Bxg2
13. Kxg2
13. c5
14. e4
14. Qc7{ Black defends against  d4 - d5 . }
15. Bg5{ Simply a developing move, Preparing  Bxf6  and  Ng4 . }( { Black has many moves at this point. Let's list some of the White's ideas. We definitely want to play on the kingside or in the center.  h2-h4  is always on the agenda, granting numerous advantages.  Qf3  preparing  d5  in the future is possible. Another little idea is  a2 - a4 , kind of slowing down the queenside play of Black. The position is balanced, but I slightly prefer White.    }15.Bf4 { would be met by }15...Bd6 { . } )
