[White "7) Symmetrical English Introduction"]
[Black "Symmetrical English: Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. c5( { By playing }1...c5 { Black mainly wants to develop the knight to  c6  in order for it to be behind the c-pawn. As many symmetrical openings, we have the move advantage, but should also be familiar with the different structures arising. } )
2. g3{ Traditionally, we prepare to position our bishop on  g2 . Further we will decide on how to develop our minor pieces, although the knight from  b1  will almost always go to  c3 . We can fight for  d2 - d4  or  b2 - b4  pawn breaks, depending on the situation. }
2. g6
3. Bg2
3. Bg7
4. Nc3
4. Nc6{ The last moves are more or less the best, so it's rather likely you will have this position on the board most of the times. }
5. a3{ I implemented this move myself and I would like to suggest it to the viewers. The idea is simple - we want to proceed with the  b2 - b4  pawnbreak, rather than  d2 - d4 . Black has several ways to deal with it: they can prevent it once and for all with  a7 - a5 , can ignore it, or prepare  b7 - b5  instead by playing  a7 - a6 . Another plan is to counter-prepare  d7 - d5 , but that's not as easy to achieve as we will see. }
