1. c4
1. c5( { By playing }1...c5 { Black mainly wants to develop the knight to  c6  in order for it to be behind the c-pawn. As many symmetrical openings, we have the move advantage, but should also be familiar with the different structures arising. } )
2. g3{ Traditionally, we prepare to position our bishop on  g2 . Further we will decide on how to develop our minor pieces, although the knight from  b1  will almost always go to  c3 . We can fight for  d2 - d4  or  b2 - b4  pawn breaks, depending on the situation. }
2. g6
3. Bg2
3. Bg7
4. Nc3
4. Nc6
5. a3{ In this chapter we will see how to fight against the  d6 - e5  setup, which in my opinion is slightly dangerous strategically for Black, but also ambitious if Black manages to get what they want.     I call it the Vigorito setup because the American International Master David Vigorito made a course here on Chessable. He is a well-established author in the chess world.    This setup is usually used by ambitious and aggressive players who like space. We have our own aces up our sleeves, though. }
5. d6{ This is usually the safest move, not allowing  b2 - b4 . Black can also start with  a7 - a5 , as it is generally their idea not caring about the  b5 - d5  weaknesses, as he counts to cover those with pieces later on. }
6. Nf3{ White can sometimes develop the Knight via  e2 - Nge2 , but it's seldom combined with the  a2 - a3  move. }( { I should mention that }6.b4?! { doesn't work here as after }6...cxb4 7.axb4 { Black can capture the pawn }7...Nxb4! 8.Qa4+ { this doesn't give White much as after }8...Nc6 9.Bxc6+ bxc6 10.Qxc6+ Bd7 { Black defends and ends up with with the Bishop pair. } )
6. e5{ Even though this move obviously weakens the  d5 -square, Black counts on playing  Nge7 - Be6 - d5  and claim dominance over this square. }
7. O-O
7. Nge7
8. b4{ It's time to strike with this move. }
8. cxb4
9. axb4
9. Nxb4
10. Ba3
10. Nbc6{ Black has nothing better, as  a7 - a5  is impossible because of  Bxb4  and the  a8 -Rook is pinned. }
11. Ne4
11. O-O( 11...Nf5 12.g4! { and the  d6 -pawn will fall eventually. } )
12. Nxd6{ White has a huge advantage. }
