2. g3{ Traditionally, we prepare to position our bishop on  g2 . Further we will decide on how to develop our minor pieces, although the knight from  b1  will almost always go to  c3 . We can fight for  d2 - d4  or  b2 - b4  pawn breaks, depending on the situation. }
2. g6
3. Bg2
3. Bg7
4. Nc3
4. Nc6
5. a3
5. b6{ This is what Peter Svidler suggests in his course. Black wants to counter our Bishop on  g2  and eventually prepare against  b2 - b4 . }
6. b4{ We take the opportunity to play our pawn break. }
6. Bb7
7. Bb2{ Black has several ideas now. }( 7.b5?! { would be a positional mistake after }7...Bxc3 8.dxc3 Na5 { and our pawns are tremendously weak. } )
7. Nh6{ This seems to be the most precise way to continue for Black, altough not really an obvious one. }
8. Rb1{ Threatening  bxc5  and  Na4  and preparing  Ba1  in some lines, as we have seen previously. }
8. Rb8{ The most logical response, defending the  b7  Bishop. }
9. Ba1{ Now that  b4  is hanging, we simply defend it. }
9. O-O
10. d3{ Having completed the  b2 - b4  pawn break, we now focus on developing our Kingside, preparing  Nf3 . }
10. Ne5{ This is usually Black's idea. }( 10...e6 { would lead to a similar position of the main line after }11.Nf3 { White simply develops. }11...Nd4 { this or  Ne5  would still be followed by the same move. }12.e3 Nxf3+ 13.Bxf3 Bxf3 14.Qxf3 { where White has some edge because the  b2 - b4  gives some extra options. } )
11. Bxb7
11. Rxb7
12. e3{ Preparing  Nf3 . }( 12.bxc5 Qa8⇆  )
12. d6( 12...Qa8 13.Nf3 { and the pin on the  h1 - a8  diagonal can always be countered by the  Nd5  jump. } )
13. Nf3
13. Nxf3+{ Sooner or later the Knights will be traded. }
14. Qxf3
14. Rd7( { Similar is }14...Qd7 15.O-O { and White has completed development. } )
15. O-O{ A typical position, Where White will build play on the queenside, while Black will try to set up some counterattack against the White King. Although I believe White is a little quicker, as  b2 - b4  has already been achieved. }
