1. c4
1. c5( { By playing }1...c5 { Black mainly wants to develop the knight to  c6  in order for it to be behind the c-pawn. As many symmetrical openings, we have the move advantage, but should also be familiar with the different structures arising. } )
2. g3{ Traditionally, we prepare to position our bishop on  g2 . Further we will decide on how to develop our minor pieces, although the knight from  b1  will almost always go to  c3 . We can fight for  d2 - d4  or  b2 - b4  pawn breaks, depending on the situation. }
2. g6
3. Bg2
3. Bg7
4. Nc3
4. Nc6
5. a3
5. e6{ This leads to the Fischer System. As you can guess, it is named after the World Champion Robert James Fischer (just to be clear!).     Black is developing the pieces behind the pawns, at the same time trying to be flexible, not creating the  d5  weakness as in the Vigorito System. They will usually try to fianchetto the  c8 -Bishop too. This system used to be considered one of the best versions of the Symmetrical English. However, White still has a chance to fight for an advantage. Let's take a look. }( 5...d6 { this is less flexible as Black will not have some immediate  d7 - d5  later on. } )
{ In case of the immediate: }6. b4{ Black has a strong reply now. }
6. Nxb4
7. axb4
7. cxb4{ When White would have to play in a gambit fashion. }
8. d4
8. bxc3
9. e3{ I believe it's not the best version for White here, as Black should develop quite comfortably. Nevertheless, it's a possibility as it has been played in some high level games. }
