[White "11) Symmetrical Fischer System 6...Nge7"]
[Black "Symmetrical Fischer System 6...Nge7 #3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. c5( { By playing }1...c5 { Black mainly wants to develop the knight to  c6  in order for it to be behind the c-pawn. As many symmetrical openings, we have the move advantage, but should also be familiar with the different structures arising. } )
2. g3{ Traditionally, we prepare to position our bishop on  g2 . Further we will decide on how to develop our minor pieces, although the knight from  b1  will almost always go to  c3 . We can fight for  d2 - d4  or  b2 - b4  pawn breaks, depending on the situation. }
2. g6
3. Bg2
3. Bg7
4. Nc3
4. Nc6
5. a3
5. e6{ This leads to the Fischer System. As you can guess, it is named after the World Champion Robert James Fischer (just to be clear!). Black is developing the pieces behind the pawns, at the same time trying to be flexible, not creating the  d5  weakness as in the Vigorito System. They will usually try to fianchetto the  c8 -Bishop too. This system used to be considered one of the best versions of Symmetrical English. However, White still has a chance to fight for advantage. Let's take a look. }( 5...d6 { this is less flexible as Black will not have some immediate  d7 - d5  later on. } )
6. Rb1
6. Nge7{ Black allows  b2 - b4  and prepares to meet it with  d6 . }( { This is more popular than the }6...a5 { move. } )
7. b4
7. cxb4
8. axb4{ Generally releasing the tension favours White, as they now have powerful b and c-pawns. }
8. a5{ This is often a possible reaction on the queenside. White can now choose between two comfortable continuations. }
9. b5{ This is a more strategically risky choice, as we leave Black with the passed a-pawn, but on the other hand we establish nice control in the center. }
9. Nb4
10. Qb3{ White gets ready to meet  d5  with  d3 , defending the  c3 -Knight in advance. }
10. d5{ Trying to break in the center. }
11. d3{ Defending  c4  and preparing  Nf3 . }
11. dxc4
12. dxc4
12. e5
13. Ba3{ Trying to eliminate the  b4 -Knight before developing our kingside. The  e4  and  b5 -pawns dominate the  e7 -Knight very well. }
13. Bf5
14. Rd1
14. Qb6
15. Bxb4{ Entering a forcing sequence. }( 15.Be4 { is another option, preparing  Nf3  and  O-O . } )
15. axb4
16. Qxb4
16. Nc6{ Black has to try to show some compensation for the pawn. }
17. Qd6
17. Rd8
18. Bxc6+{ Simplifying the position. }
18. bxc6
19. Qxd8+
19. Qxd8
20. Rxd8+
20. Kxd8
21. bxc6{ Black definitely has compensation, but White can play for two results with the two (at the moment) extra pawns and the play focused on one side of the board, which usually doesn't suit Bishops. }
