5. Nf6{ We will now discuss the so-called 'Indian line' (I coined this term myself), where Black prioritizes rough development over harmony. In the old day, this move would already be considered slightly imprecise, as Black will hardly achieve  d7 - d5 , and the Knight on  f6  kind of blocks the  g7 -Bishop for no reason if they will not push  d5 . }
6. Rb1
6. O-O{ Ignoring White's threats, Black finishes development. Now it's important for us to understand Black's idea. }
7. b4
7. cxb4
8. axb4
8. d6{ This would be quite slow, as Black will not be able to play  d7 - d5  in one move. }
9. b5{ We gain extra space on the queenside, attacking the Knight. }
9. Ne5{ Probably the best square, attacking the  c4 -pawn. }
10. d3{ White has a beautiful pawn chain, and Black will need to challenge it as quickly as possible. }
10. a6{ Black has to fight against the strong pawn chain immediately. }
11. bxa6
11. Rxa6
12. Nh3{ White will castle and have a structural advantage. It's not obvious how Black will play  b5 . In case the  d5  break appears, White will simply have a structural advantage. }
