[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) Reverse Maroczy Introduction chapter"]
[Black "Reverse Maroczy 3...Nc6 #2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. c5( { By playing }1...c5 { Black mainly wants to develop the knight to  c6  in order for it to be behind the c-pawn. As many symmetrical openings, we have the move advantage, but should also be familiar with the different structures arising. } )
2. g3{ Traditionally, we prepare to position our bishop on  g2 . Further we will decide on how to develop our minor pieces, although the knight from  b1  will almost always go to  c3 . We can fight for  d2 - d4  or  b2 - b4  pawn breaks, depending on the situation. }
2. Nf6
3. Bg2
3. Nc6( { Although in the Reverse Maroczy we will mainly analyze }3...d5 { , a great comment has pointed out this problematic move order. I would like to suggest here a rarely played continuation for White. } )
4. Nc3{ In general, if we can remain flexible with the Knight on  g1  and control the  d5 -square many times, it is both logical and aesthetically pleasant. }( 4.Nf3 { is of course possible. Here Black would continue with }4...d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 { and after }6.Nc3 { the move }6...g6 { becomes a serious option. With the Knight already on  f3  and the Black Knight still on  d5 , White has some issue developing initiative on the queenside. However, he can take some space on the kingside with }7.h4!? { hinting on  h4 - h5 . A complicated game is ahead of the players. } )
4. e6{ The challenging move, preparing  d5 . }
5. Bxc6{ A typical move in the symmetrical English, once Black played ... e7 - e6 . White wants to play on the weakened dark squares. Both recaptures have some dangers for Black. }( 5.Nf3 { This is the main response. White develops and prepares to play the logical move  d2 - d4 . }5...d5 { Black has some other slower options here, but at this point White would simply play  O-O  and  d2 - d4 . }6.cxd5 exd5 ( 6...Nxd5 { would give White a plus after }7.O-O { and  d2 - d4  next. } )7.d4 { Here however, having the Knight on  c3 , Black has several good options in my opinion, packed with a bunch of practiced theory. } )
5. bxc6{ It is clear that the Bishop on  c8  is not happy about this recapture. }
6. f4{ White once again uses the momentum to play this important move. }
6. d5{ Black has to do something in the next moves. If Black doesn't go for ugly-looking complications connected with ... d5  and sometimes ... dxc4 , White would simply expand in the center with  d3 - e4  and probably be simply better. }
7. Nf3{ Developing, as  e5  might still be one of Black's main plans. Now Black has few options, as he should decide what to do with the d-pawn. }
7. dxc4{ At this point the  c4 -pawn is kind of annoying as it doesn't allow developing our Bishop. }
8. Qa4{ This looks like the most flexible move. Not only do we want to capture on either  c4  or  c6 , we almost vacate the  d1 -square for the Knight to manoeuvre via  d1 - e3 - c4 . }
8. a5{ A difficult move. Black could also develop his kingside, but I believe his main issue is the activization of his light-squared Bishop. }( { More likely is the continuation }8...Be7 9.Qxc4 O-O 10.b3 { and White is in control of the potential ... c5 - c4  break. } )
9. Ne5
9. Be7{ Another non obvious move. Now White has to take on  c6 . }
10. Nxc6
10. Qc7{ Another important move. }
11. Nxe7+{ We remove the Bishop pair. Later White will play  b3 , in order to develop his dark-squared Bishop on  a3 . }
11. Kxe7
12. Rf1{ Preparing  b3 , without having the  h1  Rook under potential attack. }
12. Rd8{ Black develops, preparing ... Kf8 - Kg8 . }
13. b3{ It's more important to develop the pieces, instead of taking on  c4  and giving Black a tempo with ... Ba6 . }
13. cxb3
14. Ba3{ White's idea is to keep the 5-pawn structure after  d3 , and to play against the  c5  weakness. Having the  f4 -pawn there is not ideal, but the weaknesses on the light squares are not so relevant. }
14. Kf8
15. Ne4{ Exchanging the Knights, putting immediate pressure against  c5 . There is an interesting middlegame ahead of the players. }
