11. f6
12. Bd2( 12.exf6 { this looks a little too dangerous in my opinion }12...Nxf6 13.O-O O-O 14.e5! Ng4 15.Qe2 Bf5 { with ... Ne3  next, Black has clear counterplay here. } )( 12.b3 fxe5 ( 12...O-O 13.Qe2 Nxe5  )13.Ba3  )
12. fxe5
13. Qe2{ This type of closed position is also interesting to play, as Black will have to think about the double c-pawns in the long run, while the weakness of the light squares in the White's camp is quite irrelevant, as they can be easily covered with the pieces, or with the moves  h3 - g4 . }
