6. Be7( {  A)  }6...dxc4 { keeps the pawn structure healthy. }7.Qxd8+! { I prefer this approach. }( { ( }7.Qxc4 { is possible, but I think the  c6 - b7  pawn chain shouldn't cause too many problems for Black). } )7...Kxd8 8.Nbd2! { attacking the  c4 -pawn }8...Bc5! ( { ( }8...Be6 { would be a mistake for }9.Ng5! { ) } ){ Black prepares  Ke7  with the dark squared Bishop already out. }9.Nxc4 Be6 10.Nce5 { It's important to keep the dark squared Bishops alive. }( { (After }10.Na5 { Black would play }10...Bb4+ 11.Bd2 Bxd2 12.Nxd2 { and after }12...Kc7 { the king would be kind of safe.) } )10...Nbd7 ( { (If }10...Bb4+ { not }11.Bd2?! { , but }11.Kf1! { and once again the black King doesn't feel comfortable). } )11.Nd3 { retreating with a tempo. }11...Bb6 12.O-O { I like White's position. If  Ke7 ,  b3  could follow at some point, underlining the poor prospects of black's monarch. } )( {  B)  }6...Nbd7 7.cxd5 Bc5 { is possible, but after the simple }8.Qd1 Nxd5 9.e4 { Black will have to retreat the Knight from the center. After either  Nf6  or  Nc7 , White will position the queen on a comfortable square on  c2  and try to make the kingside pawns rolling, as in the line in the Slav variation. } )( {  C)  }6...c5?! { is not good as after }7.Qe5+ { the  g2 -Bishop is open and the  h1 - a8  diagonal is now more vulnerable. } )( {  D)  }6...Be6 { doesn't really threaten neither  dxc4 , because of  Qxd8  and we will transpose into some main lines, nor  c5 , as after }7.O-O c5 8.Qd3 d4 9.b4! { will destroy the freshly built center. } )
7. cxd5{ now that  c6 - c5  is a possible idea, we decide to capture on  d5 . }
7. cxd5( 7...Qxd5 { is an option to preserve the  c6 - b7  structure. }8.Nc3 Qxd4 9.Nxd4 O-O 10.O-O { Although Black is solid, there is the idea of repositioning the Knight to the annoying  a5 -square. In general White should be a little preferable. } )
8. O-O
8. Nc6
9. Qa4{ Lateral squares are usually best for the queen in the initial phase. }
9. O-O{ This is somehow comparable to the classical Tarrasch, but Black is a little more passive with the Bishop on  e7  and we can quickly put pressure on the  d5  pawn. }
10. Nc3
10. Qb6{ This is the most played move, unpinning from a possible  Rd1 . }( {  A)  }10...Be6 { looks too passive to me, after }11.Be3 { I don't see why the isolated pawn should be an asset. White will try to attack it quickly and if }11...Ng4 12.Bd4 { threatening  h3  and  Bxf6  at some point. } )( {  B)  Top engine move is }10...Bb4 { but frankly I don't see any reason to play it, as after }11.Bg5 { Black has to play }11...Bxc3 12.bxc3 h6 13.Bxf6 Qxf6 14.Nd4 { and it seems that sooner or later  Nxd4  has to be played. After }14...Nxd4 15.cxd4 { White is definitely better thanks to the weaknesses of the  d5 -pawn and the solid pawn chain. } )
11. Qb5{ It's important to play this thematic move now. }( { In case of }11.Rd1 { Black has the strong }11...a6! { preventing  Qb5 . In case of }12.Nxd5 Nxd5 13.Rxd5 Be6 14.Rd1 Rad8 { Black has an excellent compensation for the pawn, thanks to the lead in development. } )
11. d4{ This is the main and the most forcing move. }( 11...Rd8 { would be followed by }12.Qxb6 axb6 13.Rd1 d4 14.Nb5 { transposing to the main line. } )( 11...Bc5 { is possible, improving the Bishop. After }12.Qxb6 { Black should play }12...axb6! { opening the  a -file for the Rook. }13.a3 { I prefer this quiet move, eliminating the pressure along the  a -file. }13...h6 { This seems to be important now, preventing  Bg5 . We play }14.Bd2 { in order to take away the  a5 -square for the Rook once we play  Nb5 . I think White is slightly preferable, next will be  Rfd1 ,  Nb5  and Black will have to find counterplay, which is not obvious. } )
12. Qxb6
12. axb6
13. Nb5
13. Rd8{ Black defends the pawn. }( { They can also play }13...d3 { but in a position that arises after }14.exd3 Nb4 15.Be3! { Black will eventually recapture the pawn, but they will still have the b-pawns weak and our Bishops are quite powerful, eyeing the queenside. } )( 13...Bc5 { goes back to the old main line, after }14.Rd1 Rd8 15.Nc7!  )
14. Rd1{ Transposing to the main line. }
14. Bc5{ I have faced this move in my game versus Nisipeanu, and failed to find the best move here. }( { Top engine move is }14...Bg4 { provoking }15.h3 { and then going back with }15...Be6 { . I think White is better in practical terms after }16.Nfxd4 Rxa2 17.Rxa2 Bxa2 18.Be3 { as Black has to go with }18...Nd5! { a typical concrete engine idea. }19.Nf5 { we have a structural advantage and with so many pieces on the board it's much harder to play for Black. } )
15. Nc7( { Against Nisipeanu I played }15.Bf4 { , which make sense, but is countered by the concrete }15...Be6! { , which he didn't play. By starting with  15.Nc7 , White will eventually manage to prepare  a3 - b4  and to destroy the  b6-Bc5-d4  construction. } )
15. Ra5
16. Bd2
16. Ra4
17. b3
17. Ra7( 17...Ra3 { is the same. } )
18. Nb5
18. Ra8
19. a3{ After some piece dancincg, now  b4  is unavoidable. }
19. Ne4
20. b4
20. Be7
21. Be1{ A very harmonious set up for White. A correspondence game went }
21. Bf6
22. Nfxd4{ White exploits the loose Knight on  e4 . }
22. Nxd4
23. Nxd4
23. Rxd4
24. Rxd4
24. Bxd4
25. Rd1
25. Bf6( { If }25...Nxg3 26.hxg3 Bf6 27.Bc3! { And White keeps the advantage. } )
26. Bxe4
26. Rxa3
27. Kg2{ White is slightly, but surely better. }
