1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. c6{ Black tries to build a strong center by supporting the  d5  push with the  c6  pawn. Having played  g3 , we already have a clear plan of fighting it, by placing our Bishop on  g2 . }
3. d4{ This is what I will suggest in this course. White strikes in the center, as the  c6 -pawn will now take away the square for the Knight in order to kick a potentially strong Queen in the center if the  d4 -pawn gets captured. }
3. e4{ This ambitious move broke in the opening charts, becoming the modern main line. Black aims to build a strong center. }
4. a3{ This is what I will advice here. We take away the  b4  square from the  f8  Bishop and count on fighting Black's center later on. White will rely on the  f2 - f3  break if needed. }
4. d5
5. Nc3
5. Be7{ This is the move GM Arturs Neiksans suggests in his chessable course. Black doesn't hurry to develop his  g8  Knight and plays a development move. }
6. f3{ We have to start shaking the Black pawn formation. As a rule of thumb, Black shouldn't capture on  f3  unless it is need, and here they have an interesting alternative, which is 6... Nf6 . }
6. Nf6
7. Bg2
7. exf3
8. Nxf3( { Transposes to the main line after   }6...Nf6 7.Bg2 exf3 { . } )
8. O-O( 8...dxc4 { this option will be possible for Black during the next few moves. In this case we would react by occupying the center after }9.O-O O-O 10.e4 { and after the logical }10...b5 { we play brings us back to  8... dxc4 . }11.h3 { to gain some space on the kingside, improve our King and eventually start placing our pieces on the kingside. }11...Nbd7 12.Kh2 a5 13.Bf4 { At some point we might proceed with  g3 - g4  which is a typical move and eventually  Qe1 - Qg3 . A defensive idea that can create some problems here is the typical  Ra6  move preparing  b5 - b4  and eventually being ready to shift the rook to the kingside along the sixth rank once it will be possible. These positions are obviously quite double-edged, but I feel like it's easier for White to play them. } )
9. O-O
9. h6
10. Bf4
10. Be6( { Black plays a developing move, once again not hurrying with }10...dxc4 { . Here after }10...dxc4 11.e4 { White has a better version, as he may go back to the plan of  h3 - g4 . } )( { The engine says there is the move }10...a5 { , but it's hard to imagine that somebody would play such a move. First of all, after }11.cxd5 cxd5 { you really don't want for your  a -pawn to be on  a5 , as the  b5 -square now is really weak. Secondly it's quite illogical to play a rather mysterious lateral pawn move, when there is a fight in the center. On the other hand, chess now is tremendously concrete, so I wouldn't be shocked if this move would appear in an over-the-board game. } )
11. cxd5{ This is not really a move we want to play, but here it is connected to a concrete idea. Whenever the Bishop moves from  c8 , the  b7 -pawn becomes weak. }
11. cxd5( { If }11...Nxd5 { , we play }12.e4 { and enjoy our strongly supported center. } )
12. Qb3
12. g5{ This seems to be the best reply. Black tries to solve the problems by concrete means. }( 12...Nc6 { we grab the pawn with }13.Qxb7 Na5 14.Qa6 { where }14...Rb8 { is not possible, and }14...Nc4 { is well countered by }15.Ne5! { with advantage. } )( 12...Qb6 13.Qxb6 axb6 14.Nb5 { the weakness of the }b5 { square and the  b -pawns grant White an advantage. } )
{ If we retreat the Bishop }13. Bd2{ Black can develop. }
13. Nc6
14. Qxb7
14. Na5
15. Qa6
15. Nc4{ We don't have the  Ne5  counter and  Rb8  is now possible as the white Bishop doesn't guard the  b8 -square anymore. }
