*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) Introduction Reversed Dragon"]
[Black "Introduction #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. Nf6
3. Bg2
3. d5
4. cxd5
4. Nxd5{ We will call this the Reverse Dragon, as White has already decided to play  g3 - Bg2 . It is normally considered that the Dragon Sicilian, the one that can be reached with the opposite colours, should be best met with the plans involving long castle. Here Black doesn't have this opportunity, as he is a tempo down. Therefore, he will have to opt for short castle plans, and White is usually happy about that. }
5. Nc3{ We will proceed with the classical approach. White puts immediate pressure on the  d5  Knight, so Black has to react immediately. Surprisingly enough, he has several playable choices. }
5. Nb6{ This is by far the main move, which will be covered in a separate chapter. }
6. e3{ Is a fascinating line, where White goes all-in preparing  Nge2 - f4 . Although I have played this plan myself on several occasions, I would definitely advise you to discover the attacking ideas of this approach in the Simon Williams chessable course! }
