1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. Nf6
3. Bg2
3. d5{ Black enters the reversed open Sicilian territory. }
4. cxd5
4. Nxd5
5. Nc3{ By applying immediate pressure, we force Black to make a decision with the  d5 -Knight. }
5. Ne7{ This move usually alludes to the  g6 - Bg7  setup, but here White is simply better. }
6. Nf3
6. Nbc6
7. O-O
7. g6
8. b4{ Not having any  e5 - e4  ideas, Black is struggling on the queenside. }
8. Bg7
9. b5{ White can effortlessly expand. }
9. Nd4
10. e3
10. Ne6( 10...Nxf3+ 11.Bxf3 { would leave Black's minor pieces without much perspective. } )
11. Bb2{ White is simply better. }
