*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) Other 5th moves"]
[Black "5.Nc3 Nxc3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. Nf6
3. Bg2
3. d5{ Black enters the reversed open Sicilian territory. }
4. cxd5
4. Nxd5
5. Nc3{ By applying immediate pressure, we force Black to make a decision with the  d5 -Knight. }
5. Nxc3{ This concept has recently changed evaluation, especially in the open Sicilians, where White plays  Nxc6  quite often. }
6. bxc3{ The main drawback of  Nxc3  for Black is giving White a potential strong center. However, Black counts on easy development, as he now doesn't have to worry about the  d5  Knight positioning. }
6. Bd6{ This looks the best move, consolidating the  e5  pawn. }( 6...c5 { re-enters the reverse Maroczy. } )
7. Nf3
7. O-O( 7...e4? { would be both a positional mistake and a tactical blunder }8.Qa4+ { and White wins the pawn. } )
8. d4{ It's probably better to start with this move. }
8. Nd7{ This can come to mind for Black, in order to play  c6 - Qc7  later, to try to play against the  g2  Bishop. However, this would be too passive. }( 8...e4? 9.Ng5 { would be a catastrophe for Black. } )
9. O-O
9. c6
10. e4
10. Qc7
11. Nh4{ An important idea to keep in mind. Both  Nf5  and  f4  are powerful threats. }
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) Other 5th moves"]
[Black "5.Nc3 Nxc3 #2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. Nf6
3. Bg2
3. d5{ Black enters the reversed open Sicilian territory. }
4. cxd5
4. Nxd5
5. Nc3{ By applying immediate pressure, we force Black to make a decision with the  d5 -Knight. }
5. Nxc3{ This concept has recently changed evaluation, especially in the open Sicilians, where White plays  Nxc6  quite often. }
6. bxc3{ The main drawback of  Nxc3  for Black is giving White a potential strong center. However, Black counts on easy development, as he now doesn't have to worry about the  d5  Knight positioning. }
6. Bd6{ This looks the best move, consolidating the  e5  pawn. }( 6...c5 { re-enters the reverse Maroczy. } )
7. Nf3
7. O-O( 7...e4? { would be both a positional mistake and a tactical blunder }8.Qa4+ { and White wins the pawn. } )
8. d4{ It's probably better to start with this move. }
8. Nc6{ Theoretically, Black should commit a positional mistake developing this Knight in front of the  c7  pawn. Nevertheless, he counts on fighting White's central pawns with the minor pieces. Generally it's not a good approach, but here it's kind of an exception. }
9. O-O
9. exd4{ This is a strategic mistake, although people seem to play it carelessly. I would like to point out that by trading on  d4  Black doesn't exchange the central  e5 -pawn for the White's  d4 -pawn, but for White's  c3 -pawn!     This is an important finesse, so Black shouldn't go for it. }
10. cxd4
10. Re8
11. Bg5{ A move worth knowing. Moving the pawn to  f6  would create Black additional weaknesses. }
11. Qd7{ This obviously disrupts Black's development. }
12. Re1
12. Qf5{ Trying to somehow give some air to the  c8 -Bishop. }
13. Bd2{ Black should have a hard time dealing with potential  e2 - e4  threats. }
