7. O-O( 7...e4? { would be both a positional mistake and a tactical blunder }8.Qa4+ { and White wins the pawn. } )
8. d4{ It's probably better to start with this move. }
8. Nc6{ Theoretically, Black should commit a positional mistake developing this Knight in front of the  c7  pawn. Nevertheless, he counts on fighting White's central pawns with the minor pieces. Generally it's not a good approach, but here it's kind of an exception. }
9. O-O
9. Re8{ This looks like the best idea for Black. The Queen is usually meant to be on  f6 , so the Rook defends the  e5  pawn in advance. }
10. Qc2{ Eyeing on some  Ng5  ideas, at the same time giving the  d1  square to the  f1 -Rook. }
10. h6{ Black has other moves, but this should be the most useful one. }
11. Bb2{ Not rushing with  Rd1 , but connecting the Rooks. }
11. Qf6{ Preparing  Bf5 . Here I would like to illustrate another plan for White. }( 11...Bd7 12.e4 { and Black continues struggling on finding a plan. } )
12. d5{ Generally, it's not a good idea to give up on the central squares. Here we do it in order to open the  b2 -Bishop against the  f6 -Queen precisely. }
12. Nb8{ The best retreat, intending on exploiting the weakened  c5 -square. }
13. c4
13. Na6
14. Nh4{ With  e2 - e4  and  f2 - f4  plan, White will have the initiative and the  c5 -square is not too important, as the attack will take place on the kingside. }
