[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. Nf6
3. Bg2
3. d5{ Black enters the reversed open Sicilian territory. }
4. cxd5
4. Nxd5
5. Nc3{ By applying immediate pressure, we force Black to make a decision with the  d5 -Knight. }
5. Nf6{ This seemingly strange retreat has been very popular recently. The idea is to have  e5 - e4  in some lines, supported by the  f6 -Knight. }( 5...Be6 { in the case of this move, White would continue with }6.Nf3 Nc6 7.O-O { and the  e6 -Bishop will be misplaced, while d2-d4 is imminent. We will cover this line deeper in the 5... Nb6  line. } )
6. Nf3
6. Nc6{ Now White can exploit the absence of the Knight on  b6  and expand on the queenside. }
7. b4
7. e4{ This was tried, in order to capture the  b4 -pawn. }
8. Ng5
8. Bxb4
9. Ngxe4{ White remains with a potentially strong center. }
9. O-O
10. O-O
10. Nxe4{ The most logical continuation for Black. }
11. Nxe4
11. Re8{ freeing the  f8  square for the Bishop in case of  a3 . }
12. Bb2{ White doesn't rush pushing the central pawns. }
12. Be6{ The strongest set-up, preventing  e3 . }
13. d3{ sustaining the  e4  Knight, without committing to  e2 - e3 . }
13. h6{ Apparently this move has to be played, otherwise  Ng5  would be annoying. }( 13...Qd7 14.Qc1! { is a strong reply, apart from  Ng5 . White threatens both  Qg5  and  Nc5 . } )
14. a3
14. Bf8
15. Rc1
15. Na5{ The only strategic compensation for the lack of central pawns. }
16. e3{ White will proceed with  Qe2 , and eventually  f4 - f5 - f6  is a plan. }
