2. g3
2. Nc6{ Black rejects the plans connected to the quick  d7 - d5  and prefer to stop White's further  d2 - d4 . }( 2...Nf6 3.Bg2 Bc5 { is a very fashionable modern line, which will be discussed in detail, providing White two ways of dealing with it. } )
3. Nc3
3. Nf6{ This is the most natural move, preparing to develop the  f8  Bishop and to finish development by castling short. }( 3...f5 { set more of an aggressive tone for Black, but I would rather look at this as a weakening, rather than an aggressive move. The two main minuses of  f7-f5  are the weakening of the castled kingside monarch and the limitation of the  c8 -Bishop, which will now have a closed  c8 - h3  diagonal. }{ Black will have to justify any further actions by playing a quick  f5 - f4 , or expanding even more on the kingside, but that's not so easy to achieve. } )
4. Bg2{ White waits for Black's development, without showing his card. }
4. Bc5{ This leads to the so called Karpov variation. I am not sure how much Karpov himself used this weapon as Black, but rather it's consistent with his chess approach: Black develops the pieces in the most natural way, looking for harmony. White, on the other side, will try to prove Black wrong: White's pieces will be developed behind the pawns, so to be able to fight better in the center. You can't say the same for Black, who has the  c6  Knight in front of his  c7  pawn. }( 4...Bb4 5.Nd5! { is the typical reaction, and we will see the possible developments. } )
