2. g3
2. Nc6{ This move indicates that Black will probably delay the development of the  f6 -Knight and surely won't fight for a quick  d7 - d5  break. }
3. Nc3{ As anticipated,  Nc6  should usually be answered by  Nc3 , delaying  Bg2 . }
3. f5{ Black follows the principle that says it's better to develop the pieces behind the pawn. However, the f-pawn kind of represents an exception, as it also weakens the potential defenses of the future castled black King. Furthermore, Black invests a tempo on a move that is not strictly a developing one. }
4. Bg2( 4.Nf3 { with the idea to play  d2 - d4  is another way of dealing with the early  f7 - f5 . }4...Nf6 5.d4 e4 6.Nh4 { White can later develop the Bishop on  h3 , being clever. This is a concrete approach, which makes quite a sense, too. } )
4. Nf6
