6. Be7{ The purpose of this Bishop is usually to defend against the  Nd5  jumps with  d8 , guarding the  c7 -pawn. }
7. d4{ Not the only way to proceed, but the most principled. }
7. O-O
8. O-O
8. Qe8{ Black dreams of creating an attack against the white King. }
9. Nd5{ It's important to play this move now, otherwise Black would reroute the  c6 -Knight via  d8  to  e6 . }
9. Bd8
10. b3{ A strong move, focusing on the development. }
10. a5{ Top engine move, getting some space on the queenside. }( 10...Qh5 { this would be Black's logical continuation, but in reality Black has no threats. It's a healthy habit not to rush with  Nec3 , as  f4  would be possible for Black. As far as the Knight is on  e2 ,  f4  would be simply met by  exf4  and  Nxf4 . } )
11. Nec3{ As I said, White generally shouldn't rush with this move. However, since Black spent a tempo on  a7 - a5 ,  f5 - f4  is not an issue. }
11. Nxd5{ Black has other options, but mostly leading to a similar scenario. }( 11...f4 { goes nowhere, as White can simply capture everything, keeping his solid position intact. }12.dxe5 dxe5 13.exf4 { Black destroyed the center for nothing. } )
12. Bxd5+{ Not really an important move, but it's also a possibility. }
12. Kh8
13. Bg2
13. Qf7( 13...f4 { with the Bishop still on  c1 , this is simply a bad move. }14.d5! { preparing to capture the  f4 -pawn for free. }14...Ne7 15.exf4 { White is simply a pawn up, as the King is very safe. } )
14. Rb1{ A very deep move. Our  c1  Bishop guards  f4 , so it has to be kept there, as it can be considered developed. With  Rb1 , White creates the plan of  a3 - b4 , and the Rook can be improved with  Rb2  next. If  f5 - f4  is not a plan for Black, it's not so easy to suggest an active one. }
