1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. Nc6{ This move indicates that Black will probably delay the development of the  f6 -Knight and surely won't fight for a quick  d7 - d5  break. }
3. Nc3{ As anticipated,  Nc6  should usually be answered by  Nc3 , delaying  Bg2 . }
3. Bc5
4. Bg2
4. d6{ Without  Nf6  Black is trying to be flexible, especially connected to the idea we are about to see. }
5. e3{ A familiar pattern: we limit the  c5 -Bishop, preparing  Nge2 . }
5. Bf5{ This would define the position of the Bishop. }
6. a3{ Once again, we remain flexible with the d-pawn, defending against  Nb4 . }
6. a5{ This was played several times by Peruvian Grand Master Emilio Cordova. }( 6...Bd3 { leads nowhere after }7.b4 Bb6 8.Qb3 { and the  d3  Bishop alone does nothing and subsequently will be kicked, losing precious time. } )
7. d3{ Now that  Bd3  might be annoying we play this move. }
7. Nge7( 7...Nf6 { re-enters into some Karpov lines. } )
8. Nge2
8. Qd7
9. h3{ We saw that this is an important idea. }
9. O-O
10. b3{ The six pawns on the third rank control a lot of squares against the enemy pieces. Moreover, Black has to be careful about different pawn breaks. }
10. h6{ One of the many useful moves, although far from being forced. }
11. Ra2{ An idea we already saw. White wants  Rd2 - Bb2  and prepare  d3 - d4 . We can see in this line the importance of positioning the pieces behind the pawns :) I believe White is better and can improve the position, while for Black it's hard to do likewise.  Kf1 - Kg1 - Kh2  is even a plan sometimes! }
