1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. Nc6{ This move indicates that Black will probably delay the development of the  f6 -Knight and surely won't fight for a quick  d7 - d5  break. }
3. Nc3{ As anticipated,  Nc6  should usually be answered by  Nc3 , delaying  Bg2 . }
3. Bc5
4. Bg2
4. d6{ Without  Nf6  Black is trying to be flexible, especially connected to the idea we are about to see. }
5. e3{ A familiar pattern: we limit the  c5 -Bishop, preparing  Nge2 . }
5. a6{ The  a7 - a5  would be a weakening as we know, so this seems like the most natural way to give the Bishop the  a7  square. }( 5...h5 { this move doesn't really make sense here, as White can go }6.Nf3 { and  h5  will be weak. } )
6. Nge2{ Keeping the  d2 - d4  option opened. }
6. h5{ White has to be aware of this idea. }
7. d4{ As the saying goes    'The side push should be answered by a central push,'    here White gets some space in the center. }
7. Ba7
8. h3{ This is generally the best reaction, preparing  g3 - g4  in case of  h5 - h4 . However, White has to know a little bit more, because things are not so easy. }
8. h4
