9. f5{ This is the idea behind keeping the Knight on  g8 . This used to be quite an important line back in the days. White has to react appropriately. }
10. g5{ A very concrete move. White threatens to shut the Black pieces if he manages to play  f2 - f4  next. }( 10.gxf5 { could seem more of a natural response, as it used to be but Black gets what they want, opening files and granting squares for the pieces. This would justify the existence of this line. White should choose another direction. } )
10. Qxg5( 10...f4 11.Ne4! { would leave the Knight on a lovely central square, difficult to contest. } )
11. Rg1{ The nature of the position has changed dramatically. White forgets the positional ideas they had and fights for piece activity and initiative. }
11. Qd8{ Avoiding  Nd5  with tempo would be met by a strong reply for us. }
12. Bxc6+
12. bxc6
13. dxe5
13. dxe5
14. Qxd8+
14. Kxd8
15. Rxg7{ With total disaster for Black }
