[Result "*"]

1. c4{ In this chapter we will analyze the types of position characterizing KID and Dutch setups. }
1. e5{ Taking space in the center is typical for King's Indian and Dutch type of structures. Black can start with several move orders, but  e7 - e5  will always be there. }( 1...f5 { Black can obviously start with this move, immediately defining a Dutch setup. }2.g3 Nf6 3.Bg2 d6 { Black should start with this move if he wants to get a Classical Dutch setup, in order to be ready to meet  d2 - d4  with  Be7 . }3.Bg2 g6 { the Leningrad setup is characterized by the Bishop on  g7  and the pawn mass behind Black's pieces. }4.Nc3 Bg7 5.b4! { We will focus on the queenside expanding approach in the chapter, now that Black expanded with  f7 - f5  himself. } )
2. g3
2. g6{ Black will always fianchetto his Bishop, so this is the most flexible, not defining the position of the  g8  Knight yet. }( 2...d6 { as mentioned in the Karpov's and co. System, if Black starts with this move, they usually wants to go  f7 - f5  next, being now prepared for  d2 - d4  with the  Be7 . This would most probably lead us to the Classical Dutch system. } )
3. Bg2
3. Bg7
4. Nc3{ We always play the moves that are necessary first. The  g1  Knight doesn't always go directly to  f3 . }
4. d6
5. d3{ Once again we stall with the development of our  g1  Knight, generally waiting to see where Black will put his own  g8  Knight himself. }( 5.b4!? { the fact that Black hasn't played  Nc6  so far, gives White an extra option of expanding on the queenside, before developing his kingside. With the center being so quiet, this might be a profitable approach, the one that White has to keep in mind. We will see that generally playing  b2 - b4  before Black has played  a7 - a5  might be a serious idea for White. } )
5. Nc6{ This prevents  b2 - b4  and leaves the option of  Nge7 . }
6. Rb1{ Once again White doesn't define the position of the  g1 -Knight. }
6. a5
7. a3{ Now Black has to develop the  g8 -Knight. }
7. Nge7( 7...Nf6 8.Nf3 { would transpose into the Classical KID with the Knight on  f6 . } )
8. e3{ Against the Knight on  e7  we prefer to play  Nge2 . It's not an absolute rule, as there are always exceptions in chess, but it can be a mental wire that helps us remember things easier. }
