[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24) Dutch"]
[Black "Classical Dutch #3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. f5
2. g3
2. Nf6
3. Bg2
3. g6{ Instead of playing with the Bishop on  e7 , Black fianchettoes the Bishop. The difference with the KID setup, is obviously the fact, that Black has pushed  f7 - f5  prior to playing  Nf6 . As we have seen in previous chapters, this doesn't mean that it's a better version for Black. }
4. Nc3
4. Bg7
5. b4{ After analyzing several lines, I think it's best to take the opportunity to take space on the queenside right now. }
5. O-O
6. Bb2{ Defending against  Ne4  and simply developing. }
6. e5{ Black should take space in the center. }
7. d3
7. d6{ Black has other moves, but this looks the most logical development move to me. }
8. Nf3{ It's important to develop the Knight on  f3 , keeping the  e2 - d3  structure solid. This position might have been reached by several move orders. In general, I would like to say that here White wants to improve the position not only on the queenside, but also in the center. We will see how we should behave when Black start pushing the pawns on the kingside and how to proceed with White with the own play. }
8. h6{ Preparing  g6 - g5  looks like the main approach. I think Black is the most flexible move for Black. }
9. O-O
9. g5( 9...Nc6 { would force }10.b5 Ne7 { but White will proceed in a similar fashion as after }9...g5 { . } )
10. Qb3{ I wouldn't commit to  b4 - b5  yet,  Qb3  connects the Rooks and asks Black how he wants to deal with the  c4 - c5 + threat. }
10. Kh8{ I believe Black should respect the  c5 + threat, not only because of the objective strength, but also because once White will play  c5 + and  cxd6 , they will have a simple plan of penetrating along the c-file. Once there will be an open file, it's going to be hard for Black to transform the expansion of the kingside in an attack. }
11. Nd2{ It's funny if you look at the position that both players are almost avoiding each other, a kind of a distance battle! }
11. Nc6{ After all, Black has to develop this Knight somehow. }
12. e3{ Controlling the  d4 -square. }
12. f4{ I believe most of the people (including myself) will ask themself the question, what happens if Black pushes this pawn. White may become scared as Black wants to play  g4 - f3  and take a lot of space. However, this would be a strategic mistake, as it gives away many squares for White pieces, especially the  e4 -square. }
13. b5
13. Ne7
14. exf4{ It's an important detail to include in this move. Black now has an unpleasant choice. Whether they capture with the  g4 -pawn, so that no  g4 - f3  will be possible, or will capture with the  e5 -pawn and open the central files. }
14. exf4( 14...gxf4 15.d4!? { White reacts in the center. It's not a crucial move, but here it works very well. White will open even more files and the black King on  h8  start to feel the danger incoming. It's also quite obvious at this point that the White King is in no danger whatsoever. } )
15. Rfe1{ Controlling the open file. It appears to be more clever to bring the f-Rook, because we don't want to allow any  Bh3  later that might force us to exchange the light square Bishops. }
15. Ng6
16. Nce4{ The  d2 -Knight here belongs on  f3 . White has a pleasant position. It's hard to believe that Black can create any serious threats on the Kingside, considering that the  c8 -Bishop and the  a8 -Rook will take a lot of time to join the game, while the events started to take part in the center of the board. }
