5. Be7{ Black continues to develop. }
6. O-O
6. O-O{ This looks like the best move to me. Black castles in order to be ready against a quick  d2 - d4 . }( 6...a57.d4! { and  a7 - a5  would be an important waste of tempo for Black. The similar variations arising after the sequence  d4-e4  would be in favor of White compared to the main lines. } )
7. b4{ White takes space. Once again Black has a choice: whether he tries throwing pieces on the kingside through the typical plan  Qe8 - Qh5 - f4 , or try to create an even stronger central formation. }( 7.d4 { Black is ready against this. }7...e4 8.Ng5 d5 { the simplest way to consolidate in the center. }9.cxd5 Nxd5 { with  c6  next, Black should be fine. } )
7. Qe8{ A useful move, having two purposes: the first one is obviously to hint on  Qh5  aggressive ideas, while the other one is to free the  d8  square, in order to play the  Nc6 - Nd8 - Nf7  plan. }( 7...e4 { doesn't really do much, as after }8.Nd4 { Black's center will be challenged. } )
8. d3{ Having captured space with  b4 , White proceeds with this useful move. More than defending against  e5 - e4 , which isn't really a threat, we prepare  Nd2 , which is our plan as we will see. }
8. Nc6{ This is another possibility, totally ignoring the queenside. As we have seen against the KID setup, White is happy to take space on the queenside, if it's not contested. }
9. b5
9. Nd8
