10. a6{ A clever move, that sooner or later should be played. Otherwise White gets too much space. }( 10...Qh5 { we already know that here }11.e3! { is a strong move. } )
11. e3{ Having taken space on the queenside, we improve our structure in the center, preparing  Nd2 - f4 , or simply developing the  c1  Bishop connecting the Rooks, controlling  f4  once more. }
11. Nf7( 11...axb5 { would force White to find the trick in order to justify the spoilt structure. }12.Nxb5 Ne6 13.c5! { and with  Ba3  next, White has the initiative. } )
12. Bd2{ Intending the recapture on  a5  with the a-pawn in case. }
12. axb5{ Otherwise White would proceed with  Qc2 , connecting the Rooks. }
13. axb5
13. Rxa1
14. Qxa1
14. c6{ Having lost most of the illusions of the actual attack, Black plays for stability. }( 14...e4 15.Nd4! exd3 16.f4! { and the  d3 -pawn will fall, highlighting the weaknesses it has provoked. } )
15. Qb1{ Preventing  e5 - e4 , White will slowly improve on the kingside, with  Qc2  and  Ra1  next.  Ne1 - f4  is always possible, too. }
