7. Qe8{ A useful move, having two purposes: the first one is obviously to hint on  Qh5  aggressive ideas, while the other one is to free the  d8  square, in order to play the  Nc6 - Nd8 - Nf7  plan. }( 7...e4 { doesn't really do much, as after }8.Nd4 { Black's center will be challenged. } )
8. d3{ Having captured space with  b4 , White proceeds with this useful move. More than defending against  e5 - e4 , which isn't really a threat, we prepare  Nd2 , which is our plan as we will see. }
8. a6{ 'This idea was played by Ding in a classical game'. I don't know what could be a more reassuring statement in terms of preparation, so we have to take this move seriously. As far as I understand, this is generally a useful move, preventing  b4 - b5  for the moment. }( 8...f4 { would be premature, as White can simply capture the pawn }9.gxf4 { and after }9...Qh5 10.d4! { and the center will explode before Black is able to create any serious threats. } )
9. e3{ Defending against  Qh5 . }
9. Nc6
10. Rb1{ Simply defending the pawn, White keeps the option of playing  a2 - a4  in one move. }
10. Nd8{ The logical continuation for Black, bringing the Knight closer to the kingside. }
11. Nd2{ I really like this idea, played by the Chinese Xu against the same Ding. White wants to play the thematic  f2 - f4 , keeping the  f5  Black pawn where it is, so it can limit Black's minor pieces. }
11. f4{ Now that we can't capture this pawn with a piece after  exf4   exf4   Bxf4 , we have to consider how to react. }
12. exf4{ Capturing once, opening up the center. }
12. exf4
13. Nf3{ We go back with our defender, threatening to capture on  f4  with the Bishop. }( 13.gxf4 { would be a terrible positional mistake. I hope the fact that White is a pawn up doesn't mislead the reader here - }13.gxf4 { is a bad move. } )
13. fxg3
14. fxg3{ Black's initiative didn't do much: White will have a strong center now and the pieces will harmoniously support it. The  c1  Bishop can be considered as already developed, as White can play  Rb2  in order to improve the Rook. We have seen a similar idea in the Karpov System section. }
