1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. g6{ I believe this is the most flexible move order for Black. Whenever they play  Nc6  or  Nf6 , they remove options from the table. I have to say that in this kind of quiet position it's not a big deal, but it's a healthy habit to pay attention to move orders, as you improve in chess. }
3. Bg2
3. Bg7
4. Nc3
4. d6{ Once again Black this looks the most flexible. }
5. d3{ As mentioned in the introduction, White waits for Black to decide where to put the  g8 -Knight. }
5. Nf6{ The classical approach. Modern chess has spoiled the fans with fancy move orders, h-pawn early marches, general principles being ignored, but we can't forget them. After all, from  f6  the Knight controls  e4  and  d5  squares in the center. }
6. Nf3{ Once the Knight is on  f6 , we develop our Knight on  f3 . Again, this is not forced, but as a matter of patterns, this might help us recognise the type of position we want to reach. }
6. O-O
7. O-O
7. Nh5{ Black can totally ignore the queenside and go straight for the kill on the kingside. Let's see how we should handle this approach. }
8. e4{ White fights against  f7 - f5 . }
8. Nc6( 8...f5? { would be a disaster: }9.exf5! gxf5 { this is how Black would ideally like to recapture, but after }10.Nxe5! { the  h5 -Knight would be undefended. } )
9. h3{ Now that  f7 - f5  is unlikely to be working, White prevents  Bg4  and prepares  Be3 , followed by the  d3 - d4  break. }
9. h6{ A useful move once again, preventing both  Ng5  and  Bg5  that might be annoying. }
10. Be3
10. Be6{ Preventing  d4 . }( 10...Nd4 { is a typical positional mistake in my opinion. Or at least White gets quite a favorable pawn structure. }11.Bxd4! exd4 12.Ne2 { the  d4 -pawn closes Black's pieces. White also gets a perceived pawn majority on the kingside (a term that I used to call it, although I might be the only one).    Imagine dividing the board in two parts: the one from the  a -file to the  d file, the second one from the  e -file way to the  h -file. Black's extra pawn on the left side is not as perceived as the extra pawn on the right side. } )
11. b3{ Simply protecting the  c4  pawn and preparing  d2 - d4 . }
11. Nd4{ Black can't really allow  d3 - d4 , otherwise White gets a very comfortable position. }
12. Bxd4
12. exd4
13. Ne2
13. c5
14. b4{ Before pushing our majority on the kingside, it might be a good idea to take some space on the queenside. }
14. b6( 14...cxb4 { it's hard to believe that destroying the pawn structure can lead anywhere good. } )
15. Qd2{ White has a very pleasant position, as it's hard for Black to find a plan. White will remove the Knight from  f3  and push the majority with  g4  and  f4 . }
