5. Nf6{ The classical approach. Modern chess has spoiled the fans with fancy move orders, h-pawn early marches, general principles being ignored, but we can't forget them. After all, from  f6  the Knight controls  e4  and  d5  squares in the center. }
6. Nf3{ Once the Knight is on  f6 , we develop our Knight on  f3 . Again, this is not forced, but as a matter of patterns, this might help us recognise the type of position we want to reach. }
6. O-O
7. O-O
7. Nc6{ Not allowing  b2 - b4  at the moment, this is the most played move here. }
8. Rb1{ White proceeds with the plan. It's much better to start with  Rb1  instead of  a3 , for two reasons: first, we take out the Rook from the  a1 - g7  diagonal, so no  e4  funky stuff is possible opening the  g7 -Bishop; secondly, in case Black doesn't play  a5 , but after  b4  will play  a6 , we can play  a2 - a4  there in one move. }
8. a5{ Forcing  a2 - a3  in order to play  b4 . This way Black will open the a-file for the Rook. }
9. a3{ White should insist in playing  b2 - b4 . The plans with  b2 - b3   Bb2  might be a little bit too slow compared to the Karpov System, where Black doesn't have a clear on the kingside. }
9. Nd4{ This is the favourite engine move. However, it involves more of a defensive strategy from Black. }
10. b4{ White proceeds with the plan. }( 10.Nxd4 exd4 { doesn't really help White as Black will put a brake on White's initiative on the queenside with  a5 - a4  next. } )
10. axb4
11. axb4{ It is true that Black has the open 'a' file, but having White more space on the queenside, it's very likely that he will end up being the one controlling it. }
11. c6{ As we have seen, this is the logical follow-up of the move 9... Nd4 . Black wants to fight for the  c6 - d5  light squares in the center. }
12. b5
12. Nxf3+{ The principled approach. }
13. Bxf3
13. d5{ Black basically dares White to prove he is the one favourite to conquer the light squares. In a practical game Black has to be careful in order to play in such fashion. }
14. bxc6{ We include this in order to activate our  b5  Rook, as now the fight for the  d5  square is priority number 1. }
14. bxc6
15. cxd5
15. cxd5
16. Bg5{ An unpleasant pin to face for Black. }
16. Ra5{ A strong move, defending the  d5  pawn and x-raying the  g5 -Bishop. }( 16...Be6 17.Rb5 { shouldn't be allowed by Black. } )
17. Qd2{ Defending the Bishop on  g5  and preventing  h7 - h6 . With  Rfc1  next, it will be an interesting middlegame. Black's center might be either a strong asset, restricting White's pieces, or a liability that they have to take care of. }
