[White "26) KID ...Nge7 setups"]
[Black "7...Nge7 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4
1. e5
2. g3
2. g6
3. Bg2
3. Bg7
4. Nc3
4. Nc6{ Just in case, Black starts with  Nc6 , in order to avoid  b4 . On the other hand, they can forget about expanding in the center with  c6 - d5 . }( 4...d6 5.b4!? { it is probably not a big deal, but we have often seen that this might be a possibility for White. } )
5. d3{ White doesn't commit to  Nf3  just yet. }
5. d6{ Black keeps the options, too. }( 5...Nge7 { would reveal the cards too soon, as White can choose between several options, including }6.e4!?  )
6. Rb1{ White keeps playing on the queenside. }( 6.e4 { is called the Botvinnik System. The idea is to create a powerful configuration of pieces, behind the pawns. I myself have played it many times with success and enjoyed studying the several plans. I think it's a valid system, providing White excellent chances of advantage. This approach is presented in the Simon Williams chessable course, so check it out! I will focus on a more flexible    choice, where White doesn't decide on the central structure yet. } )
6. a5{ We have already seen that this is usually the best approach for Black. }
7. a3{ A generally useful move, preparing  b2 - b4 . }
7. Nge7{ Black finally decides on to play  Nge7 . This generally means that they want to proceed in a more balanced way, preparing  Be6  and more often  d6 - d5 , rather than  f7 - f5 . }( 7...Nf6 8.Nf3 { would redirect us to the classical KID system. } )
8. e3{ It seems more clever to me to develop the Knight on  e2 , whenever it's possible. I am not sure about the objective advantage of this choice, but it's easier for White to continue in my opinion. }
8. O-O{ The most logical move. }
9. Nge2
9. Be6{ Now White has to decide on how to react against the  d6 - d5  possibility. }
10. Nd5{ The general knowledge suggests playing this move, in order to stop  d6 - d5 . I wouldn't say that it's absolutely true, but here we make Black life a little harder. }
10. h5{ This annoying move is often times suggested by the engine. The idea is to meet 11.0-0 with 11... h4 , and give some more space for the King. White should change plans here. }
11. e4{ I believe this is the right way. White transposes into a Botvinnik system, where  h7 - h5  shouldn't really help Black, as now the  f7 - f5  plan might often be weakening too much Black's position. White also opens the dark-squared Bishop, who will be able to exploit the recently weakened  g5  square. }
11. a4{ Black takes the opportunity to block White's play on the queenside. }
12. O-O{ Preparing  f2 - f4 . }( 12.Ndc3 { would be too greedy, as Black would seize the initiative with }12...Nd4! { connected to the  h4 - Bg4  ideas. } )
12. Qd7{ Multi-purpose move, forming a battery and protecting the  a4  pawn in order to prepare  Na5  in some lines. Black also connects the Rooks. }( 12...h4 { would now be pointless, as after }13.gxh4! { Black is simply a pawn down. White will be able to support it with  Bg5 , or prepare to exchange it with a well-timed  h4 - h5  later on. } )
13. Bd2( 13.Be3 { White would like to ideally play  Be3 - Qd2 , but with this space Black has on both flanks thanks to the  a4  and  h5 -pawns, }13...Nd4 { would be strong, as now }14.Nxd4 exd4 { would attack the Bishop on  e3 . } )
13. Kh7{ A very clever move, preparing  Ng8 . }( 13...Nd4 { would now be a positional mistake, as after }14.Nxd4 exd4 15.Nf4 { White can keep the structural advantage and can later on play  f2 - f4 . } )
14. Kh1{ Another strong preparatory move. The King will be better on  h1 , avoiding some tactics. White is finally ready to play  f4 . }
