10. Qd7{ By far the most played move. However, I would say that the ideas with  Bh3  are not so dangerous here, as Black wouldn't have any pieces in order to create threats around the White King. }( 10...Qc8 11.O-O Bg4 12.Qc2 { . } )( 10...f5 { would be a positional mistake, as  f5 - f4  is never a real move in the future for Black. White can also play  f2 - f4  in the future. The pawn on  f5  limits Black's minor pieces. } )
11. O-O
11. Nd8{ This is one of the main ideas. Black wants to exchange the Knight on, without giving up the light-squared Bishop. }( 11...Bh3 { would be a mistake. }12.Bxh3! Qxh3 13.Nxc7 { with only the Queen on  h3 , White doesn't have to worry. } )
12. e4{ Once again this move is thematic and strong. }
12. Nxd5( 12...Nc8 { allows }13.Bh6!? { White will eliminate the  g7 -Bishop and prepare  d3 - d4 . } )
13. cxd5{ We have seen this reply several times. White opens the 'c' file, targeting the  c7  pawn weakness. }
13. Bh3{ Having foreseen this idea, White has put the pawns on the light squares, which is the right strategy here. }
14. Nc3
14. Bxg2
15. Kxg2
15. f5
16. f3{ Black has no attack, while White will organize the play along the c-file against the  c7  pawn. The  d8  Knight will also need time to be more useful. }
