1. c4
1. b6{ This move is obviously meant to prevent  2.g3 . Black is ready to play hedgehog-type structures with the bishop on  b7 , which will put pressure along the  h1 - a8  diagonal. }
2. Nc3{ White develops the knight first, not committing in the center. }
2. Bb7{ The most flexible move for Black. }
3. e4{ White starts with  3.e4 , intending to build a Botvinnik type of setup:  Nge2- g3 -Bg2 . }
3. c5( 3...Nf6 4.f3! { would transpose to the main lines. } )
4. Nge2
4. Nc6( 4...e5 { totally closes the center, but White will have the  f2-f4  break, while Black has a terrible bishop on  b7 . } )( { Also note that }4...Nf6 5.f3! { would lead to a similar position as after  4...Nc6 . } )
5. d4{ White creates the Maroczy bind structure, with his pawns on  e4  and  c4 . }
5. cxd4{ Black has to eliminate this pawn. }
6. Nxd4
6. e6{ The best way to proceed, is freeing the  f8 -bishop. }
7. Be3{ The most natural square for the bishop. }
7. Nf6
8. Nxc6{ Eliminating the  c6 -knight immediately. }
8. Bxc6
9. f3{ Leads to a pleasant position for White. }
