1. c4
1. b6{ This move is obviously meant to prevent  2.g3 . Black is ready to play hedgehog-type structures with the bishop on  b7 , which will put pressure along the  h1 - a8  diagonal. }
2. Nc3{ White develops the knight first, not committing in the center. }
2. Bb7{ The most flexible move for Black. }
3. e4{ White starts with  3.e4 , intending to build a Botvinnik type of setup:  Nge2- g3 -Bg2 . }
3. e5{ A logical move, contesting space in the center. }
4. Nf3{ White decides to go for a more classical development. The main idea is to make the  d2 - d4  break work. }
4. Nc6
5. a3{ By now it should be familiar to the reader that this is not an aggressive move, but a prophylaxis against potential  Bb4 . }
5. Nd4{ A stunning move, based on concrete lines. Strategically it would be a dangerous decision, as often times engine suggestions do appear. }( 5...Nf6 6.d3 { would leave the  f6 -knight misplaced. Instead of the quick  d4  plan, White will simply develop with  g3-Bg2  and prepare the  f2-f4  push later on, as Black's minor pieces are really awkward. } )
6. d3{ Threatening  Nxd4 , as now  e4  is defended. }
6. Bd6{ Another paradoxical move. }( 6...Nxf3+ 7.Qxf3 { Might seem like the idea after  5...Nd4 , but here White would take space on the kingside, while the main problem of Black, the bishop on  b7 , still exists. } )
7. Nxd4
7. exd4( { The point is that after the most logical }8.Ne2 c5! { Black's idea is to bring back the  b7 -bishop to life by breaking in the center with  f7-f5!  } )
8. Nb5{ White has to go for the most direct line. }
8. Be5{ Saving the  d4 -pawn and the bishop itself. }
9. f4{ Taking space and starting to move right side majority. }
9. Bf6{ Now suddenly the  b5 -knight is in trouble, so White should give him a way to escape. }
10. a4
10. a6
11. Na3
11. Be7{ The dance of the dark-squared bishop continues. }
12. Be2
12. Bb4+( { This is normal. Finally the Bishop will probably be exchanged. Black wants to play  ...Ne7  and  ...f5 . The immediate }12...f5 { is met by }13.Bh5 g6 14.Bf3 Bb4 15.Bd2 Bxd2 16.Qxd2 Nf6 17.O-O O-O 18.e5 { . Again, we have our majority. } )
13. Bd2
13. Bxd2+
14. Qxd2{ A typical position, where White has the right side majority. We are better, but not as much as in other lines. }
