4. Nge2{ Threatening  d2 - d4 , as  Bb4  would be pointless. }( 4.d4 { is the main reply here, but I don't like allowing Black to attack my center so early. }4...Bb4! { White should be ready to enter some very risky lines when there is no need. I've experienced that Black is quite happy to play this move order, so we should deny them the pleasure to do so. } )
4. Nf6
5. f3{ White prepares to expand in the center with  d2 - d4 . }
5. Be7{ Is an interesting approach. Black wants to castle first and then fight White's pawn center. }( { Note that }5...c5 6.d4 cxd4 7.Nxd4 { would be once again redirected to  3...c5 . } )
6. d4( 6.e5 { would be a premature commitment due to }6...Nh5 7.d4 d6 { and White will have to give up part of the center for no good reason. } )
6. O-O
7. d5{ Physically blocking the  d7 - d5  possibility. Now Black has several tries in order to shake White's center and try to exploit their temporary lead in development. }( { After }7.Be3 d5 8.cxd5 exd5 9.e5 Ne8! { Black has this square for the knight and the position is not as bad as it seems for Black. } )
7. exd5{ The most obvious move, opening the center. }
8. cxd5
8. d6{ Preparing  c7 - c6 . }
9. Nf4{ White develops, controlling the  d5 -square once more. }
9. c6{ Black has to fight in the center, otherwise they are strategically lost. }
10. dxc6
10. Nxc6
11. Be3( 11.Bc4 Ne5! { would lead nowhere. } )
11. d5{ It's absolutely White to open the center immediately. }
12. Nfxd5{ White has to capture with the piece on  d5 . }
12. Nxd5
13. Qxd5{ Threatening to exchange the queens. }
13. Qc7{ Black obviously keeps the queens. }
14. Be2{ There are several ways to proceed with White. If they manage to castle and put the rook in the center they would simply be a pawn up, as the  f3 - e4  pawn structure is very efficient against the opponent's pieces. }
14. Rfd8{ Black's counterplay is based on the dark squares and especially on the  Nd4  jump. }
15. Qb3{ Exploiting the fact that  Nd4  would lose to  Bxd4  and  Nb5 , White puts the queen on a closed file. }
15. Na5
16. Qb5{ And in order to keep chasing the White's queen, Black will have to misplace the pieces too much. }
