1. c4
1. c5( { By playing }1...c5 { Black mainly wants to develop the knight to  c6  in order for it to be behind the c-pawn. As many symmetrical openings, we have the move advantage, but should also be familiar with the different structures arising. } )
2. g3{ Traditionally, we prepare to position our bishop on  g2 . Further we will decide on how to develop our minor pieces, although the knight from  b1  will almost always go to  c3 . We can fight for  d2 - d4  or  b2 - b4  pawn breaks, depending on the situation. }
2. Nc6
3. Bg2
3. g6
4. e3{ A slightly weird move order. White defines his intensions of where to develop his  g1  Knight. Another idea is to play  Ne2  and later  Nbc3  so Black has no  Bxc3  ideas. }
4. Bg7
5. Ne2
5. d6( 5...e6 { this is probably more sound here, as Black wants to copy White's moves. Nevertheless, my opponent is known to be an aggressive player, so I wasn't expecting him to play for some dry symmetry. } )
6. Nbc3
6. h5{ This was the first bell to ring to me, tellin that my opponent didn't just want to sit and wait. }
7. h3{ The best reaction, not weakening any squares. }
7. e5{ Once again, the most aggressive approach. }
8. a3{ Postponing  d2 - d4 , as we will see why. }
8. a5{ Trying to stop  b2 - b4  once and for all. I think it's already dubious. }( { Probably better was a developing move, such as }8...Nge7 { my opponent probably didn't want to allow me }9.b4 cxb4 10.axb4 Nxb4 11.O-O { White has compensation and an easy game. } )
9. d4{ Not necessary, but I wanted to play energetic, as I managed to spare some tempi and my opponent weakened his position with  h5  and  a5 . }
9. cxd4
10. exd4
10. Nge7{ A clear mistake. }( { Better was to play }10...exd4 { Accepting an ugly pawn structure. }11.Nd5 { this was my idea during the game, as now }11...Nf6 12.Bg5 { would exploit the drawbacks of  h7 - h5 . } )
